{"title_page": "Green Mountain Race Track", "text_new": "{{short description|Former race track in Vermont, United States}}\n{{coord|42.756006|-73.233438|type:landmark_region:US-VT|format=dms|display=title}}'''Green Mountain Race Track''' was an [[United States|American]] [[horse racing]] and a [[Greyhound racing in the United States|greyhound racing]] track located in [[Pownal, Vermont|Pownal]], [[Bennington County, Vermont|Bennington County]], [[Vermont]] that operated from 1963 to 1993.\n\n==History==\n\n[[Thoroughbred]] and [[standardbred]] [[horse racing]] events were held until 1976, when thoroughbred racing was replaced by [[greyhound racing]]. One year later, standardbred racing was also discontinued, and the track exclusively featured greyhound racing until closing altogether in 1992 amid pressure from [[animal rights]] activists, who objected to greyhound racing as cruel (Vermont banned the sport in 1995.)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140409235659/http://urbanpostmortem.wordpress.com:80/2012/09/27/relics-from-a-broken-racetrack/|title=Relics From A Broken Racetrack {{!}} Obscure Vermont|date=2014-04-09|access-date=2018-05-29}}</ref>\n\nSince closing as a racetrack, the site has hosted live events occasionally, including a [[music festival|rock concert]] in the [[Lollapalooza]] series in 1996, and antique car shows from 2005 to 2008,\n\nShortly after its closing, on May 7, 2004, the {{convert|144|acre|km2|adj=on}} property went on sale on [[eBay]] with a listed price of $2.5 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/GREEN-MOUNTAIN-RACE-TRACK-FOR-SALE-12139|title=Green Mountain Race Track For Sale|last=link|first=Harness|access-date=2018-05-29|language=en-US}}</ref> It was quickly bought by Progress Partners Ltd. in a $1 million deal with the previous track owner, John C. Tiegtens<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.iberkshires.com/story/16314/A-diverse-outlook-for-Pownal-racetrack.html|title=A diverse outlook for Pownal racetrack|access-date=2018-05-29}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018 ===\n\nAround January, of 2018 mortgage holder ''Bayview Loan Serving, LLC, of Coral Gables, Fla.,'' filed a lawsuit in ''Bennington Superior Court Civil Division'' seeking to foreclose on the former ''Green Mountain Race Track property''. The lawsuit named the current owner, ''Green Mountain Race Track, LLC'', a former track ownership group; two other mortgage holders, and the entities involved with the solar array on the property that was installed in 2013. ''Bayview'', the lending service seeks for foreclosure over the unpaid balance on a mortgage on the 144-acre track site off Route 7 that dates back to 2004. This very loan was modified in August 2009, that added some accumulated interest, after a similar foreclosure complaint that had been also filed by ''Bayview''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.benningtonbanner.com/stories/lending-firm-seeks-to-foreclose-on-former-race-track-site,529281|title=Lending firm seeks to foreclose on former Green Mountain Race Track site|work=The Bennington Banner|access-date=2018-05-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe future for the track is unclear, but some proposed plans are believed to include a mix of energy-efficient companies, a [[farmers' market]] facility, and facilities to accommodate large events.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct horse racing venues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Defunct greyhound racing venues in the United States]]\n\n\n{{horseracing-venue-stub}}\n{{Vermont-sports-venue-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Former race track in Vermont, United States}}\n{{coord|42.756006|-73.233438|type:landmark_region:US-VT|format=dms|display=title}}'''Green Mountain Race Track''' was an [[United States|American]] [[horse racing]] and a [[Greyhound racing in the United States|greyhound racing]] track located in [[Pownal, Vermont|Pownal]], [[Bennington County, Vermont|Bennington County]], [[Vermont]] that operated from 1963 to 1993.\n\n==History==\n\n[[Thoroughbred]] and [[standardbred]] [[horse racing]] events were held until 1976, when thoroughbred racing was replaced by [[greyhound racing]]. One year later, standardbred racing was also discontinued, and the track exclusively featured greyhound racing until closing altogether in 1992 amid pressure from [[animal rights]] activists, who objected to greyhound racing as cruel (Vermont banned the sport in 1995.)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140409235659/http://urbanpostmortem.wordpress.com:80/2012/09/27/relics-from-a-broken-racetrack/|title=Relics From A Broken Racetrack {{!}} Obscure Vermont|date=2014-04-09|access-date=2018-05-29}}</ref>\n\nSince closing as a racetrack, the site has hosted live events occasionally, including a [[music festival|rock concert]] in the [[Lollapalooza]] series in 1996, and antique car shows from 2005 to 2008, \n\nShortly after its closing, on May 7, 2004, the {{convert|144|acre|km2|adj=on}} property went on sale on [[EBay|eBay]] with a listed price of $2.5 million<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.harnesslink.com/News/GREEN-MOUNTAIN-RACE-TRACK-FOR-SALE-12139|title=Green Mountain Race Track For Sale|last=link|first=Harness|access-date=2018-05-29|language=en-US}}</ref>. It was quickly bought by Progress Partners Ltd. in a $1 million deal with the previous track owner, John C. Tiegtens<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.iberkshires.com/story/16314/A-diverse-outlook-for-Pownal-racetrack.html|title=A diverse outlook for Pownal racetrack|access-date=2018-05-29}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018 ===\n\nAround January, of 2018 mortgage holder ''Bayview Loan Serving, LLC, of Coral Gables, Fla.,'' filed a lawsuit in ''Bennington Superior Court Civil Division'' seeking to foreclose on the former ''Green Mountain Race Track property''. The lawsuit named the current owner, ''Green Mountain Race Track, LLC'', a former track ownership group; two other mortgage holders, and the entities involved with the solar array on the property that was installed in 2013. ''Bayview'', the lending service seeks for foreclosure over the unpaid balance on a mortgage on the 144-acre track site off Route 7 that dates back to 2004. This very loan was modified in August 2009, that added some accumulated interest, after a similar foreclosure complaint that had been also filed by ''Bayview''<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.benningtonbanner.com/stories/lending-firm-seeks-to-foreclose-on-former-race-track-site,529281|title=Lending firm seeks to foreclose on former Green Mountain Race Track site|work=The Bennington Banner|access-date=2018-05-29|language=en}}</ref>.\n\nThe future for the track is unclear, but some proposed plans are believed to include a mix of energy-efficient companies, a [[farmers' market]] facility, and facilities to accommodate large events. \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct horse racing venues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Defunct greyhound racing venues in the United States]]\n{{horseracing-venue-stub}}\n{{Vermont-sports-venue-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Green_Mountain_Race_Track"}
{"title_page": "Steven Bonnar", "text_new": "{{short description|Scottish politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Steven Bonnar\n| image = Official portrait of Steven Bonnar MP crop 2.jpg\n| caption = Bonnar in 2019\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill (UK Parliament constituency)|Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill]]\n| term_start = 12 December 2019\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Hugh Gaffney]]\n| successor = \n| majority = 5,624 (11.6%)\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = \n| party = [[Scottish National Party]]\n| alma_mater = \n| Local councillor = \n| office1 = \n| office2 = \n| order = \n| incumbent = \n| status = \n| district = \n}}\n'''Steven Bonnar''' is a [[Scottish National Party]] (SNP) politician. He has served as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill (UK Parliament constituency)|Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill]] since the [[2019 United Kingdom general election in Scotland|2019 general election]].\n\nBonnar was a SNP [[councillor]] in the Thorniewood ward of [[North Lanarkshire]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/snp-wins-north-lanarkshire-by-election-1-3827414 |title=SNP wins North Lanarkshire by-election |first=Andrew |last=Whitaker |work=[[The Scotsman]] |date=10 July 2015 |accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref> He defeated the incumbent Labour candidate [[Hugh Gaffney]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/S14000011|title=General Election 2019: Coatbridge, Chryston & Bellshill Parliamentary constituency |work=BBC News |accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref> When [[Oath of Allegiance (United Kingdom)|swearing in]] to the House of Commons, he crossed his fingers to protest having to affirm allegiance to the monarchy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/snp-mp-steven-bonnar-crosses-fingers-during-swearing-in-ceremony-1-5064333|title=SNP MP Steven Bonnar crosses fingers during swearing in ceremony|website=www.scotsman.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref>\n\nIn [https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/snps-steven-bonnar-celtic-flag-21889835 April 2020] Bonnar got into an aggressive altercation with his neighbour.\n\n<br />\n\n== References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.snp.org/steven_bonnar profile] on SNP website\n* {{Twitter}}\n{{UK MP links\n| parliament   = steven-bonnar/4748\n| hansard      = \n| hansardcurr  =\n| guardian     =\n| publicwhip   = Steven_Bonnar&mpc=Coatbridge%2C_Chryston_and_Bellshill&house=commons\n| theywork     = 25861\n| record       =\n| bbc          = \n| journalisted =\n}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Hugh Gaffney]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill (UK Parliament constituency)|Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill]]|years=[[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{SNP MPs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bonnar, Steven}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scottish National Party MPs]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Scottish National Party councillors]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Parliament of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:House of Commons of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Scottish National Party politicians]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-UK-MP-stub}}\n{{UK-MP-2019-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Scottish politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Steven Bonnar\n| image = Official portrait of Steven Bonnar MP crop 2.jpg\n| caption = Bonnar in 2019\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill (UK Parliament constituency)|Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill]]\n| term_start = 12 December 2019\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Hugh Gaffney]]\n| successor = \n| majority = 5,624 (11.6%)\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = \n| party = [[Scottish National Party]]\n| alma_mater = \n| Local councillor = \n| office1 = \n| office2 = \n| order = \n| incumbent = \n| status = \n| district = \n}}\n'''Steven Bonnar''' is a [[Scottish National Party]] (SNP) politician. He has served as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill (UK Parliament constituency)|Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill]] since the [[2019 United Kingdom general election in Scotland|2019 general election]].\n\nBonnar was a SNP [[councillor]] in the Thorniewood ward of [[North Lanarkshire]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/snp-wins-north-lanarkshire-by-election-1-3827414 |title=SNP wins North Lanarkshire by-election |first=Andrew |last=Whitaker |work=[[The Scotsman]] |date=10 July 2015 |accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref> He defeated the incumbent Labour candidate [[Hugh Gaffney]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/S14000011|title=General Election 2019: Coatbridge, Chryston & Bellshill Parliamentary constituency |work=BBC News |accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref> When [[Oath of Allegiance (United Kingdom)|swearing in]] to the House of Commons, he crossed his fingers to protest having to affirm allegiance to the monarchy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/snp-mp-steven-bonnar-crosses-fingers-during-swearing-in-ceremony-1-5064333|title=SNP MP Steven Bonnar crosses fingers during swearing in ceremony|website=www.scotsman.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref>\n\nIn [https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/snps-steven-bonnar-celtic-flag-21889835 April 2020] Bonnar got into an aggressive altercation with his neighbour over his Celtic flag which Bonnar hangs from his house.\n\n<br />\n\n== References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.snp.org/steven_bonnar profile] on SNP website\n* {{Twitter}}\n{{UK MP links\n| parliament   = steven-bonnar/4748\n| hansard      = \n| hansardcurr  =\n| guardian     =\n| publicwhip   = Steven_Bonnar&mpc=Coatbridge%2C_Chryston_and_Bellshill&house=commons\n| theywork     = 25861\n| record       =\n| bbc          = \n| journalisted =\n}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Hugh Gaffney]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill (UK Parliament constituency)|Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill]]|years=[[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{SNP MPs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bonnar, Steven}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scottish National Party MPs]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Scottish National Party councillors]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Parliament of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:House of Commons of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Scottish National Party politicians]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-UK-MP-stub}}\n{{UK-MP-2019-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Frlamont", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steven_Bonnar"}
{"title_page": "Operation Pastorius", "text_new": "{{short description|Attempted WWII German sabotage operation against the Continental U.S.}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{operational plan\n| name        = Operation Pastorius\n| partof      = the [[American Theater (1939-1945)|American Theater]] of [[World War II]]\n| image       = [[File:Nazi saboteur trial.jpg|325px]]\n| caption     = The trial of the captured Germans, July 1942.\n| objective   = [[Sabotage]] American economic infrastructure\n| date        = June 1942\n| executed_by = Nazi Germany\n| outcome     = Failed\n}}\n{{North American Theater}}\n\n'''Operation Pastorius''' was a failed [[Nazi Germany|German]] [[Espionage|intelligence]] plan for [[sabotage]] inside the [[United States]] during [[World War II]]. The operation was staged in June 1942 and was to be directed against strategic American economic targets. The operation was named by [[Admiral]] [[Wilhelm Canaris]], chief of the German ''[[Abwehr]]'', for [[Francis Daniel Pastorius]], the leader of the first organized settlement of Germans in America.\n\n==Background==\nAfter the Japanese [[attack on Pearl Harbor]] on December 7, 1941, followed by [[German declaration of war against the United States (1941)|Nazi Germany's declaration of war on the United States]] four days later<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/germany-declares-war-on-the-united-states|title=Germany declares war on the United States - Dec 11, 1941 - HISTORY.com|publisher=|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref> (and the [[United States declaration of war upon Germany (1941)|United States' declaration of war on Germany]] in response), [[Adolf Hitler|Hitler]] authorized a mission to sabotage the American war effort and attack civilian targets to [[Demoralization (warfare)|demoralize]] the American civilian population inside the United States.<ref>{{cite book |title=Shadow Enemies: Hitler's Secret Terrorist Plot Against the United States |author=Alex Abella, Scott Gordon |date=January 2003 |page=[https://archive.org/details/shadowenemieshit00abel_0/page/17 17] |publisher=The Lyons Press |isbn=1-5857-4722-X |url=https://archive.org/details/shadowenemieshit00abel_0/page/17 }}</ref> The mission was headed by Admiral [[Wilhelm Canaris]], chief of the German ''Abwehr''. Canaris recalled that during [[World War I]], he organized the sabotage of French installations in Morocco, and entered the United States with other German agents to plant bombs in New York arms factories, including the [[Black Tom explosion|destruction of munitions supplies at Black Tom Island]], in 1916. He hoped that Operation Pastorius would have the same kind of success they had in 1916.<ref>{{cite book |title=Peculiar Liaisons in War, Espionage, and Terrorism of the Twentieth Century |author=John Craig |date=2 February 2004 |page=170 |publisher=Algora Publishing |isbn=0-8758-6331-0 }}</ref>\n\n==Agents==\nRecruited for Operation Pastorius were eight German residents who had lived in the United States. Two of them, [[Ernst Burger]] and [[Herbert Hans Haupt|Herbert Haupt]], were American citizens. The others, [[George John Dasch]], Edward John Kerling, [[Richard Quirin]], Heinrich Harm Heinck, Hermann Otto Neubauer, and Werner Thiel, had worked at various jobs in the United States. All eight were recruited into the ''Abwehr'' [[military intelligence]] organization and were given three weeks of intensive sabotage training in the [[Oberkommando der Wehrmacht|German High Command]] school on an estate at [[Quenzsee|Quenz Lake]], near [[Berlin]], [[Germany]]. The agents were instructed in the manufacture and use of [[Explosive material|explosives]], [[Incendiary device|incendiaries]], [[Blasting cap|primers]], and various forms of mechanical, chemical, and electrical delayed timing devices. Considerable time was spent developing complete background \"histories\" they were to use in the United States. They were encouraged to converse in English and to read American newspapers and  magazines to hone their English and familiarity with current American events and culture.<ref name=\"Foes\">{{cite book |title=Insidious Foes: The Axis Fifth Column and the American Home Front |author=Francis MacDonnell |date=2 November 1995 |page=131 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=0-1950-9268-6 }}</ref>\n\n==Mission==\n\nTheir mission was to stage sabotage attacks on American economic targets: [[hydroelectric plant]]s at [[Niagara Falls]]; the [[Alcoa|Aluminum Company of America]]'s plants in [[Illinois]], [[Tennessee]], and [[New York (state)|New York]]; [[McAlpine Locks and Dam|locks]] on the [[Ohio River]] near [[Louisville, Kentucky]]; the [[Horseshoe Curve (Pennsylvania)|Horseshoe Curve]], a crucial railroad pass near [[Altoona, Pennsylvania]], as well as the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]]'s [[Altoona Works|repair shops]] at Altoona;<ref>[http://www.trainweb.org/horseshoecurve-nrhs/Guide.htm Horseshoe Curve, NRHS - Railfan's Guide to the Altoona Area](Requires Java 1.6 as of 1 January 2009]</ref> a [[cryolite]] plant in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia]]; [[Hell Gate Bridge]] in New York; and [[Pennsylvania Station (Newark)|Pennsylvania Station]] in [[Newark, New Jersey]]. The agents were also instructed to spread a wave of terror by planting explosives on [[bridge]]s, [[Train station|railroad station]]s, water facilities, and [[Public space|public places]]. They were given [[counterfeit]] [[birth certificate]]s, [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] Cards, [[Conscription|draft]] deferment cards, nearly $175,000 in American money, and [[driver's license]]s, and put aboard two [[U-boat]]s to land on the east coast of the U.S.<ref name=\"Foes\" />\n\nBefore the mission began, it was in danger of being compromised, as George Dasch, head of the team, left sensitive documents behind on a train, and one of the agents when drunk announced to patrons at a bar in [[Paris]] that he was a secret agent.<ref>{{cite book |last= Dobbs |first= Michael |title= Saboteurs: The Nazi Raid on America |url= https://archive.org/details/saboteursnazirai00dobb |url-access= registration |publisher= [[Alfred A. Knopf|Knopf]] |date=February 2004 |isbn= 978-0-375-41470-1}}</ref>\n\nOn the night of June 12, 1942, the first submarine to arrive in the U.S., {{GS|U-202||2}},<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uboat.net/boats/u202.htm|title=The Type VIIC boat U-202 - German U-boats of WWII - uboat.net|publisher=|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref> landed at [[Amagansett, New York]], which is about 100 miles east of [[New York City]], on [[Long Island]], at what today is Atlantic Avenue beach. It was carrying Dasch and three other saboteurs (Burger, Quirin, and Heinck). The team came ashore wearing [[Uniforms and insignia of the Kriegsmarine|German Navy uniform]]s so that if they were captured, they would be classified as [[prisoners of war]] rather than [[espionage|spies]].<ref>[http://www.vanderbiltlawreview.org/content/articles/2013/01/Kent_66_Vand_L_Rev_153.pdf Judicial Review for Enemy Fighters: The Court\u2019s Fateful Turn in Ex parte Quirin, the Nazi Saboteur Case] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203001757/http://www.vanderbiltlawreview.org/content/articles/2013/01/Kent_66_Vand_L_Rev_153.pdf |date=3 December 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"Battle\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gq-pOED4TSUC&pg=PT98&source=gbs_toc_r&cad=3#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Scorpions: The Battles and Triumphs of FDR's Great Supreme Court Justices |author=Noah Feldman |date=8 November 2010 |page=186 |publisher=[[Hachette Book Group USA]] |isbn=0-4465-8057-0 |accessdate=25 July 2013}}</ref> They also brought their explosives, primers and incendiaries, and buried them along with their uniforms, and put on civilian clothes to begin an expected two-year campaign in the sabotage of American defense-related production.<ref>[https://www.fbi.gov/libref/historic/famcases/nazi/nazi.htm Federal Bureau of Investigation: George John Dasch and the Nazi Saboteurs], FBI Famous Cases</ref>\n\nWhen Dasch was discovered amidst the dunes by unarmed [[United States Coast Guard|Coast Guardsman]] John C. Cullen, Dasch offered Cullen a $260 bribe.<ref>\nElke Frenzel, [http://www.spiegel.de/international/zeitgeist/0,1518,716753,00.html Hitler's Unfulfilled Dream of a New York in Flames] ''[[Der Spiegel]]'' 16 September 2010</ref> Cullen feigned cooperation but reported the encounter. An armed patrol returned to the site but found only the buried equipment; the Germans had taken the [[Long Island Rail Road]] from the [[Amagansett (LIRR station)|Amagansett station]] into [[Manhattan]], where they checked into a hotel. A massive [[Manhunt (military)|manhunt]] was begun.\n\nThe other four-member German team headed by Kerling landed without incident at [[Ponte Vedra Beach, Florida]], south of [[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]] on June 16, 1942. They came on {{GS|U-584||2}}, another submarine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uboat.net/boats/u584.htm|title=The Type VIIC boat U-584 - German U-boats of WWII - uboat.net|publisher=|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref> This group came ashore wearing [[bathing suit]]s but wore German Navy hats. After landing ashore, they threw away their hats, put on civilian clothes, and started their mission by boarding trains to [[Chicago, Illinois]] and [[Cincinnati, Ohio]].<ref name=\"Battle\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1372973/Revealed-The-secret-Nazi-operation-Pastorius-land-German-soldiers-U-S-soil-sabotage-war-effort-world-war-two.html |title=Hitler sent German U-boat carrying secret agents to terrorise New York during World War Two (but it got wedged off Long Island) |author=Kevin Dougherty |date=5 April 2011 |publisher=[[Daily Mail]] |accessdate=26 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe two teams were to meet on July 4 in a hotel in Cincinnati to coordinate their sabotage operations.<ref>Page 130, The Florida Historical Quarterly, Volume 49</ref>\n\n==Betrayal==\nDasch called Burger into their upper-story hotel room and opened a window, saying they would talk, and if they disagreed, \"only one of us will walk out that door\u2014the other will fly out this window.\" Dasch told him he had no intention of going through with the mission, hated [[Nazism]], and planned to report the plot to the FBI. Burger agreed to defect to the United States immediately.<ref name=\"McCann2006\">{{cite book|author=Joseph T. McCann|title=Terrorism on American Soil: A Concise History of Plots and Perpetrators from the Famous to the Forgotten|url=https://archive.org/details/terrorismonameri00jose|url-access=registration|year=2006|publisher=Sentient Publications|isbn=978-1-59181-049-0|pages=[https://archive.org/details/terrorismonameri00jose/page/81 81]\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Dobbs2007\">{{cite book|author=Michael Dobbs|title=Saboteurs: The Nazi Raid on America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TWOKF8-fZtAC&pg=PA119|date=18 December 2007|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-42755-7|pages=119\u2013}}</ref>\n\nOn June 15, Dasch phoned the New York office of the FBI to explain who he was, but hung up when the agent answering doubted his story. Four days later, he took a train to [[Washington, DC]] and walked into FBI headquarters, where he gained the attention of Assistant Director D.{{nbsp}}M. Ladd by showing him the operation's budget of $84,000 cash.<ref name=\"Dobbs2007\"/><ref>{{cite book |title=Helluva Town: The Story of New York City During World War II |author=Richard Goldstein |date=13 April 2010 |page=40 |publisher=[[Free Press (publisher)|Free Press]] |isbn=1-4165-8996-1 }}</ref> Besides Burger, none of the other German agents knew they were betrayed. Over the next two weeks, Burger and the other six were arrested.  FBI Chief, Hoover, made no mention that Dasch had turned himself in, and claimed credit for the FBI for cracking the spy ring.<ref name=\"wapomonument\" />\n\n==Mugshots==\n<gallery class=\"center\" heights=\"175px\" mode=\"packed\">\nFile:George John Dasch.jpg|[[George John Dasch]]\nFile:Ernest Peter Burger.jpg|[[Ernst Peter Burger]]\nFile:Herbert Haupt - mugshot.jpg|[[Herbert Hans Haupt|Herbert Haupt]]\nFile:Heinrich Heinck - mugshot.jpg|[[Heinrich Heinck]]\nFile:Edward John Kerling - mugshot.jpg|[[Eddie Kerling]]\nFile:Herman Otto Neubauer.jpg|[[Herman Otto Neubauer]]\nFile:Richard Quirin - mugshot.jpg|[[Richard Quirin]]\nFile:Werner Thiel - mugshot.jpg|[[Werner Thiel]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Trial and execution==\nFearful that a civilian court would be too lenient, President Roosevelt issued Executive Proclamation 2561 on 2 July 1942 creating a [[military tribunal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=16281|title=Franklin D. Roosevelt: Proclamation 2561\u2014Denying Certain Enemies Access to the Courts|publisher=|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref> to prosecute the Germans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jacksonville.com/news/metro/2010-07-12/story/agents-picked-ponte-vedra-landing-point-1942 |title=A Look Back: Nazi agents picked Ponte Vedra as landing point in 1942 |author=Jessie-Lynne Kerr |date=12 July 2010 |work=[[The Florida Times-Union]]}}</ref> Placed before a seven-member military commission, the Germans were charged with the following offenses:\n\n:* 1) Violating the [[law of war]];\n:* 2) Violating Article 81 of the [[Articles of War#United States|Articles of War]], defining the offense of corresponding with or giving intelligence to the enemy;\n:* 3) Violating Article 82 of the Articles of War, defining the offense of spying; and\n:* 4) [[Conspiracy]] to commit the offenses alleged in the first three charges.\n\nThe trial was held in Assembly Hall #1 on the fifth floor of the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] building in Washington D.C. on 8 July 1942.<ref>{{cite book|title=Roosevelt's Secret War: FDR and World War II Espionage |author=Joseph E. Persico |page=204 | publisher=[[Random House]]| date=22 October 2002 | isbn=0-3757-6126-8}}</ref> Lawyers for the accused, who included [[Lauson Stone]] and [[Kenneth Royall]], attempted to have the case tried in a civilian court but were rebuffed by the [[United States Supreme Court]] in ''[[Ex parte Quirin]]'', 317 U.S. 1 (1942), a case that was later cited as a precedent for the trial by military commission of any [[unlawful combatant]] against the United States.\n\nThe trial for the eight defendants ended on 1 August 1942. Two days later, all were found guilty and sentenced to death. Roosevelt commuted Burger's sentence to life in prison and Dasch's to 30 years because they had turned themselves in and provided information about the others. The others were executed on  8 August 1942 in the [[electric chair]] on the third floor of the District of Columbia jail and buried in a [[potter's field]] in the [[Blue Plains (Washington, D.C.)|Blue Plains]] neighborhood in the [[Anacostia]] area of Washington.\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe failure of Operation Pastorius led Hitler to rebuke Admiral Canaris and no sabotage attempt was ever made again in the United States. During the remaining years of the war, the Germans only once more dispatched agents to the United States by submarine. In November 1944, as part of [[Operation Elster]] a German submarine, [[German submarine U-1230|U-1230]], dropped two [[SS-Reichssicherheitshauptamt|RSHA]] spies off the coast of [[Maine]] to gather intelligence on American manufacturing and technical progress. The FBI captured both men shortly after.<ref name=\"Miller2013\">{{cite book|author=Robert A. Miller|title=A True Story of An American Nazi Spy: William Curtis Colepaugh|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ndSkplZUUh8C&pg=PA73&dq=%22There+is+not+one+word+of+reference+to+sabotaging+the+atom+bomb%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwifjZb-wJrVAhWDgj4KHXZ9CXcQ6AEIJjAA#v=onepage&q=%22There%20is%20not%20one%20word%20of%20reference%20to%20sabotaging%20the%20atom%20bomb%22&f=false|date=27 February 2013|publisher=Trafford Publishing|isbn=978-1-4669-8219-2|pages=73\u2013}}</ref> These agents benefited from the calmer state of public nerves in the later years of the war and received prison sentences rather than execution.<ref>{{cite book |title=Insidious Foes: The Axis Fifth Column and the American Home Front |author=Francis MacDonnell |date=2 November 1995 |page=133 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=0-1950-9268-6 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1948, President [[Harry S. Truman]] granted executive clemency to Dasch and Burger on the condition that they be deported to the [[American Zone of Occupation#American Zone of Occupation|American Zone of occupied Germany]]. They were not welcomed back in Germany, as they were regarded as traitors who had caused the death of their [[Comrade|comrades]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Shoot or hang themselves? |url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-7859070.html|newspaper=Der Spiegel|number=15|language=German|date=6 April 1998}}</ref> Although they had been promised pardons by Hoover in exchange for their cooperation, both men died without ever receiving them{{Explain-wrap|date=March 2020|reason=Who are \"them\"?}}. Dasch died in 1992 at the age of 89 in [[Ludwigshafen]], [[Germany]]. Burger died in 1975.\n\nSometime in the 1960s or 1970s, the [[National Socialist White People's Party]] placed an unauthorized monument to the executed spies in a thicket in southwest Washington, D.C. on National Park Service land. It went largely unknown and ignored for several decades; the Park Service removed it in 2010.<ref name=\"wapomonument\">{{cite news |last=Cox |first=John Woodrow |date=June 23, 2017 |title=Six Nazi spies were executed in D.C. White supremacists gave them a memorial \u2014 on federal land. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/retropolis/wp/2017/06/23/six-nazi-spies-were-executed-in-d-c-white-supremacists-gave-them-a-memorial-on-federal-land/ |work=The Washington Post |access-date=June 23, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Duquesne Spy Ring]]\n*''[[They Came to Blow Up America]]'', a 1943 film based on Operation Pastorius, starring [[George Sanders]]\n*''[[Saboteur (film)|Saboteur]]'', a 1942 film revolving around acts of sabotage on the US mainland during World War II.\n*[[New York at War]], military parade held at same time\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n;Bibliography\n{{external media | width = 210px | align = right | headerimage= | video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?181143-1/saboteurs-nazi-raid-america ''Booknotes'' interview with Michael Dobbs on ''Saboteurs: The Nazi Raid on America'', 28 March 2004], [[C-SPAN]]}}\n*Dobbs, Michael, ''Saboteurs: The Nazi Raid on America,'' New York: Knopf, 2004. {{ISBN|0-375-41470-3}}\n*Rachlis, Eugene, ''They Came to Kill: The Story of Eight Nazi Saboteurs in America'', New York: Random House, 1961.\n*[[Joseph E. Persico|Persico, Joseph E.]], ''Roosevelt's Secret War: FDR and World War II Espionage'', New York:Random House, 2001, pp.&nbsp;199\u2013205. {{ISBN|0-375-50246-7}}\n*[https://www.fbi.gov/libref/historic/famcases/nazi/nazi.htm Federal Bureau of Investigation: George John Dasch and the Nazi Saboteurs]\n*[http://www.usswashington.com/dl10ju42.htm Lippmann, David H., ''World War II Plus 55, June 10-13th, 1942'']\n*[http://www.montauklife.com/history/history_night_of_the_nazis.html Montauk Life: The Night of the Nazis]\n*[https://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/html/historics/USSC_CR_0317_0001_ZS.html Cornell University School of Law: ''Ex Parte Quirin'' (summary)]\n*Samaha, Joel, ''et al.'' (eds.), ''Transcript of Proceedings before the Military Commission to Try Persons Charged with Offenses against the Law of War and the Articles of War, Washington D.C., 8 to 31 July 1942'', Minneapolis: University of Minnesota, 2004. [http://www.soc.umn.edu/~samaha/nazi_saboteurs/indexnazi.htm]\n*Abella, Alex & Gordon, Scott, ''Shadow Enemies: Hitler's Secret Terrorist Plot Against the United States'', Guilford, CT: Lyons Press, 2002. {{ISBN|1-58574-722-X}}\n\n'''Further information'''\n*[http://www.thisamericanlife.org/Radio_Episode.aspx?sched=1019 The Facts Don't Matter] An hour-long ''This American Life'' radio episode (original air date 3/12/2004) about the events leading up to ''Ex parte Quirin''\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Operation Pastorius}}\n*[http://ghostsofdc.org/2012/02/09/six-nazi-saboteurs-executed-in-washington/ Six Nazi  Saboteurs Executed in Washington] - Ghosts of DC history blog\n*{{IMDb title|id=0036426 |title= They Came to Blow Up America}} - a 1943 film about saboteurs, led by a German-American, landing on Long Island\n*{{cite newspaper |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/03/nyregion/john-cullen-coast-guardsman-who-detected-spies-dies-at-90.html |title= John Cullen, Coast Guardsman Who Detected Spies, Dies at 90 |author= Richard Goldstein |date= September 2, 2011 |work= The New York Times}}\n\n[[Category:1942 in the United States]]\n[[Category:World War II espionage]]\n[[Category:Economic warfare]]\n[[Category:United States military law]]\n[[Category:Abwehr operations]]\n[[Category:Military operations of World War II involving Germany|Pastorius]]\n[[Category:American Theater of World War II]]\n[[Category:1942 in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:1942 in Florida]]\n[[Category:1942 in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Germany\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:June 1942 events]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Attempted WWII German sabotage operation against the Continental U.S.}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{operational plan\n| name        = Operation Pastorius\n| partof      = the [[American Theater (1939-1945)|American Theater]] of [[World War II]]\n| image       = [[File:Nazi saboteur trial.jpg|325px]]\n| caption     = The trial of the captured Germans, July 1942.\n| objective   = [[Sabotage]] American economic infrastructure\n| date        = June 1942\n| executed_by = Nazi Germany\n| outcome     = Failed\n}}\n{{North American Theater}}\n\n'''Operation Pastorius''' was a failed [[Nazi Germany|German]] [[Espionage|intelligence]] plan for [[sabotage]] inside the [[United States]] during [[World War II]]. The operation was staged in June 1942 and was to be directed against strategic American economic targets. The operation was named by [[Admiral]] [[Wilhelm Canaris]], chief of the German ''[[Abwehr]]'', for [[Francis Daniel Pastorius]], the leader of the first organized settlement of Germans in America.\n\n==Background==\nAfter the Japanese [[attack on Pearl Harbor]] on December 7, 1941, followed by [[German declaration of war against the United States (1941)|Nazi Germany's declaration of war on the United States]] four days later<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/germany-declares-war-on-the-united-states|title=Germany declares war on the United States - Dec 11, 1941 - HISTORY.com|publisher=|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref> (and the [[United States declaration of war upon Germany (1941)|United States' declaration of war on Germany]] in response), [[Adolf Hitler|Hitler]] authorized a mission to sabotage the American war effort and attack civilian targets to [[Demoralization (warfare)|demoralize]] the American civilian population inside the United States.<ref>{{cite book |title=Shadow Enemies: Hitler's Secret Terrorist Plot Against the United States |author=Alex Abella, Scott Gordon |date=January 2003 |page=[https://archive.org/details/shadowenemieshit00abel_0/page/17 17] |publisher=The Lyons Press |isbn=1-5857-4722-X |url=https://archive.org/details/shadowenemieshit00abel_0/page/17 }}</ref> The mission was headed by Admiral [[Wilhelm Canaris]], chief of the German ''Abwehr''. Canaris recalled that during [[World War I]], he organized the sabotage of French installations in Morocco, and entered the United States with other German agents to plant bombs in New York arms factories, including the [[Black Tom explosion|destruction of munitions supplies at Black Tom Island]], in 1916. He hoped that Operation Pastorius would have the same kind of success they had in 1916.<ref>{{cite book |title=Peculiar Liaisons in War, Espionage, and Terrorism of the Twentieth Century |author=John Craig |date=2 February 2004 |page=170 |publisher=Algora Publishing |isbn=0-8758-6331-0 }}</ref>\n\n==Agents==\nRecruited for Operation Pastorius were eight German residents who had lived in the United States. Two of them, [[Ernst Burger]] and [[Herbert Hans Haupt|Herbert Haupt]], were American citizens. The others, [[George John Dasch]], Edward John Kerling, [[Richard Quirin]], Heinrich Harm Heinck, Hermann Otto Neubauer, and Werner Thiel, had worked at various jobs in the United States. All eight were recruited into the ''Abwehr'' [[military intelligence]] organization and were given three weeks of intensive sabotage training in the [[Oberkommando der Wehrmacht|German High Command]] school on an estate at [[Quenzsee|Quenz Lake]], near [[Berlin]], [[Germany]]. The agents were instructed in the manufacture and use of [[Explosive material|explosives]], [[Incendiary device|incendiaries]], [[Blasting cap|primers]], and various forms of mechanical, chemical, and electrical delayed timing devices. Considerable time was spent developing complete background \"histories\" they were to use in the United States. They were encouraged to converse in English and to read American newspapers and  magazines to hone their English and familiarity with current American events and culture.<ref name=\"Foes\">{{cite book |title=Insidious Foes: The Axis Fifth Column and the American Home Front |author=Francis MacDonnell |date=2 November 1995 |page=131 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=0-1950-9268-6 }}</ref>\n\n==Mission==\n\nTheir mission was to stage sabotage attacks on American economic targets: [[hydroelectric plant]]s at [[Niagara Falls]]; the [[Alcoa|Aluminum Company of America]]'s plants in [[Illinois]], [[Tennessee]], and [[New York (state)|New York]]; [[McAlpine Locks and Dam|locks]] on the [[Ohio River]] near [[Louisville, Kentucky]]; the [[Horseshoe Curve (Pennsylvania)|Horseshoe Curve]], a crucial railroad pass near [[Altoona, Pennsylvania]], as well as the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]]'s [[Altoona Works|repair shops]] at Altoona;<ref>[http://www.trainweb.org/horseshoecurve-nrhs/Guide.htm Horseshoe Curve, NRHS - Railfan's Guide to the Altoona Area](Requires Java 1.6 as of 1 January 2009]</ref> a [[cryolite]] plant in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia]]; [[Hell Gate Bridge]] in New York; and [[Pennsylvania Station (Newark)|Pennsylvania Station]] in [[Newark, New Jersey]]. The agents were also instructed to spread a wave of terror by planting explosives on [[bridge]]s, [[Train station|railroad station]]s, water facilities, and [[Public space|public places]]. They were given [[counterfeit]] [[birth certificate]]s, [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] Cards, [[Conscription|draft]] deferment cards, nearly $175,000 in American money, and [[driver's license]]s, and put aboard two [[U-boat]]s to land on the east coast of the U.S.<ref name=\"Foes\" />\n\nBefore the mission began, it was in danger of being compromised, as George Dasch, head of the team, left sensitive documents behind on a train, and one of the agents when drunk announced to patrons at a bar in [[Paris]] that he was a secret agent.<ref>{{cite book |last= Dobbs |first= Michael |title= Saboteurs: The Nazi Raid on America |url= https://archive.org/details/saboteursnazirai00dobb |url-access= registration |publisher= [[Alfred A. Knopf|Knopf]] |date=February 2004 |isbn= 978-0-375-41470-1}}</ref>\n\nOn the night of June 12, 1942, the first submarine to arrive in the U.S., {{GS|U-202||2}},<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uboat.net/boats/u202.htm|title=The Type VIIC boat U-202 - German U-boats of WWII - uboat.net|publisher=|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref> landed at [[Amagansett, New York]], which is about 100 miles east of [[New York City]], on [[Long Island]], at what today is Atlantic Avenue beach. It was carrying Dasch and three other saboteurs (Burger, Quirin, and Heinck). The team came ashore wearing [[Uniforms and insignia of the Kriegsmarine|German Navy uniform]]s so that if they were captured, they would be classified as [[prisoners of war]] rather than [[espionage|spies]].<ref>[http://www.vanderbiltlawreview.org/content/articles/2013/01/Kent_66_Vand_L_Rev_153.pdf Judicial Review for Enemy Fighters: The Court\u2019s Fateful Turn in Ex parte Quirin, the Nazi Saboteur Case] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203001757/http://www.vanderbiltlawreview.org/content/articles/2013/01/Kent_66_Vand_L_Rev_153.pdf |date=3 December 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"Battle\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gq-pOED4TSUC&pg=PT98&source=gbs_toc_r&cad=3#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Scorpions: The Battles and Triumphs of FDR's Great Supreme Court Justices |author=Noah Feldman |date=8 November 2010 |page=186 |publisher=[[Hachette Book Group USA]] |isbn=0-4465-8057-0 |accessdate=25 July 2013}}</ref> They also brought their explosives, primers and incendiaries, and buried them along with their uniforms, and put on civilian clothes to begin an expected two-year campaign in the sabotage of American defense-related production.<ref>[https://www.fbi.gov/libref/historic/famcases/nazi/nazi.htm Federal Bureau of Investigation: George John Dasch and the Nazi Saboteurs], FBI Famous Cases</ref>\n\nWhen Dasch was discovered amidst the dunes by unarmed [[United States Coast Guard|Coast Guardsman]] John C. Cullen, Dasch offered Cullen a $260 bribe.<ref>\nElke Frenzel, [http://www.spiegel.de/international/zeitgeist/0,1518,716753,00.html Hitler's Unfulfilled Dream of a New York in Flames] ''[[Der Spiegel]]'' 16 September 2010</ref> Cullen feigned cooperation but reported the encounter. An armed patrol returned to the site but found only the buried equipment; the Germans had taken the [[Long Island Rail Road]] from the [[Amagansett (LIRR station)|Amagansett station]] into [[Manhattan]], where they checked into a hotel. A massive [[Manhunt (military)|manhunt]] was begun.\n\nThe other four-member German team headed by Kerling landed without incident at [[Ponte Vedra Beach, Florida]], south of [[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]] on June 16, 1942. They came on {{GS|U-584||2}}, another submarine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uboat.net/boats/u584.htm|title=The Type VIIC boat U-584 - German U-boats of WWII - uboat.net|publisher=|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref> This group came ashore wearing [[bathing suit]]s but wore German Navy hats. After landing ashore, they threw away their hats, put on civilian clothes, and started their mission by boarding trains to [[Chicago, Illinois]] and [[Cincinnati, Ohio]].<ref name=\"Battle\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1372973/Revealed-The-secret-Nazi-operation-Pastorius-land-German-soldiers-U-S-soil-sabotage-war-effort-world-war-two.html |title=Hitler sent German U-boat carrying secret agents to terrorise New York during World War Two (but it got wedged off Long Island) |author=Kevin Dougherty |date=5 April 2011 |publisher=[[Daily Mail]] |accessdate=26 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe two teams were to meet on July 4th in a hotel in Cincinnati to coordinate their sabotage operations.<ref>Page 130, The Florida Historical Quarterly, Volume 49</ref>\n\n==Betrayal==\nDasch called Burger into their upper-story hotel room and opened a window, saying they would talk, and if they disagreed, \"only one of us will walk out that door\u2014the other will fly out this window.\" Dasch told him he had no intention of going through with the mission, hated [[Nazism]], and planned to report the plot to the FBI. Burger agreed to defect to the United States immediately.<ref name=\"McCann2006\">{{cite book|author=Joseph T. McCann|title=Terrorism on American Soil: A Concise History of Plots and Perpetrators from the Famous to the Forgotten|url=https://archive.org/details/terrorismonameri00jose|url-access=registration|year=2006|publisher=Sentient Publications|isbn=978-1-59181-049-0|pages=[https://archive.org/details/terrorismonameri00jose/page/81 81]\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Dobbs2007\">{{cite book|author=Michael Dobbs|title=Saboteurs: The Nazi Raid on America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TWOKF8-fZtAC&pg=PA119|date=18 December 2007|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-42755-7|pages=119\u2013}}</ref>\n\nOn June 15, Dasch phoned the New York office of the FBI to explain who he was, but hung up when the agent answering doubted his story. Four days later, he took a train to [[Washington, DC]] and walked into FBI headquarters, where he gained the attention of Assistant Director D.{{nbsp}}M. Ladd by showing him the operation's budget of $84,000 cash.<ref name=\"Dobbs2007\"/><ref>{{cite book |title=Helluva Town: The Story of New York City During World War II |author=Richard Goldstein |date=13 April 2010 |page=40 |publisher=[[Free Press (publisher)|Free Press]] |isbn=1-4165-8996-1 }}</ref> Besides Burger, none of the other German agents knew they were betrayed. Over the next two weeks, Burger and the other six were arrested.  FBI Chief, Hoover, made no mention that Dasch had turned himself in, and claimed credit for the FBI for cracking the spy ring.<ref name=\"wapomonument\" />\n\n==Mugshots==\n<gallery class=\"center\" heights=\"175px\" mode=\"packed\">\nFile:George John Dasch.jpg|[[George John Dasch]]\nFile:Ernest Peter Burger.jpg|[[Ernst Peter Burger]]\nFile:Herbert Haupt - mugshot.jpg|[[Herbert Hans Haupt|Herbert Haupt]]\nFile:Heinrich Heinck - mugshot.jpg|[[Heinrich Heinck]]\nFile:Edward John Kerling - mugshot.jpg|[[Eddie Kerling]]\nFile:Herman Otto Neubauer.jpg|[[Herman Otto Neubauer]]\nFile:Richard Quirin - mugshot.jpg|[[Richard Quirin]]\nFile:Werner Thiel - mugshot.jpg|[[Werner Thiel]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Trial and execution==\nFearful that a civilian court would be too lenient, President Roosevelt issued Executive Proclamation 2561 on 2 July 1942 creating a [[military tribunal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=16281|title=Franklin D. Roosevelt: Proclamation 2561\u2014Denying Certain Enemies Access to the Courts|publisher=|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref> to prosecute the Germans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jacksonville.com/news/metro/2010-07-12/story/agents-picked-ponte-vedra-landing-point-1942 |title=A Look Back: Nazi agents picked Ponte Vedra as landing point in 1942 |author=Jessie-Lynne Kerr |date=12 July 2010 |work=[[The Florida Times-Union]]}}</ref> Placed before a seven-member military commission, the Germans were charged with the following offenses:\n\n:* 1) Violating the [[law of war]];\n:* 2) Violating Article 81 of the [[Articles of War#United States|Articles of War]], defining the offense of corresponding with or giving intelligence to the enemy;\n:* 3) Violating Article 82 of the Articles of War, defining the offense of spying; and\n:* 4) [[Conspiracy]] to commit the offenses alleged in the first three charges.\n\nThe trial was held in Assembly Hall #1 on the fifth floor of the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] building in Washington D.C. on 8 July 1942.<ref>{{cite book|title=Roosevelt's Secret War: FDR and World War II Espionage |author=Joseph E. Persico |page=204 | publisher=[[Random House]]| date=22 October 2002 | isbn=0-3757-6126-8}}</ref> Lawyers for the accused, who included [[Lauson Stone]] and [[Kenneth Royall]], attempted to have the case tried in a civilian court but were rebuffed by the [[United States Supreme Court]] in ''[[Ex parte Quirin]]'', 317 U.S. 1 (1942), a case that was later cited as a precedent for the trial by military commission of any [[unlawful combatant]] against the United States.\n\nThe trial for the eight defendants ended on 1 August 1942. Two days later, all were found guilty and sentenced to death. Roosevelt commuted Burger's sentence to life in prison and Dasch's to 30 years because they had turned themselves in and provided information about the others. The others were executed on  8 August 1942 in the [[electric chair]] on the third floor of the District of Columbia jail and buried in a [[potter's field]] in the [[Blue Plains (Washington, D.C.)|Blue Plains]] neighborhood in the [[Anacostia]] area of Washington.\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe failure of Operation Pastorius led Hitler to rebuke Admiral Canaris and no sabotage attempt was ever made again in the United States. During the remaining years of the war, the Germans only once more dispatched agents to the United States by submarine. In November 1944, as part of [[Operation Elster]] a German submarine, [[German submarine U-1230|U-1230]], dropped two [[SS-Reichssicherheitshauptamt|RSHA]] spies off the coast of [[Maine]] to gather intelligence on American manufacturing and technical progress. The FBI captured both men shortly after.<ref name=\"Miller2013\">{{cite book|author=Robert A. Miller|title=A True Story of An American Nazi Spy: William Curtis Colepaugh|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ndSkplZUUh8C&pg=PA73&dq=%22There+is+not+one+word+of+reference+to+sabotaging+the+atom+bomb%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwifjZb-wJrVAhWDgj4KHXZ9CXcQ6AEIJjAA#v=onepage&q=%22There%20is%20not%20one%20word%20of%20reference%20to%20sabotaging%20the%20atom%20bomb%22&f=false|date=27 February 2013|publisher=Trafford Publishing|isbn=978-1-4669-8219-2|pages=73\u2013}}</ref> These agents benefited from the calmer state of public nerves in the later years of the war and received prison sentences rather than execution.<ref>{{cite book |title=Insidious Foes: The Axis Fifth Column and the American Home Front |author=Francis MacDonnell |date=2 November 1995 |page=133 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=0-1950-9268-6 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1948, President [[Harry S. Truman]] granted executive clemency to Dasch and Burger on the condition that they be deported to the [[American Zone of Occupation#American Zone of Occupation|American Zone of occupied Germany]]. They were not welcomed back in Germany, as they were regarded as traitors who had caused the death of their [[Comrade|comrades]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Shoot or hang themselves? |url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-7859070.html|newspaper=Der Spiegel|number=15|language=German|date=6 April 1998}}</ref> Although they had been promised pardons by Hoover in exchange for their cooperation, both men died without ever receiving them{{Explain-wrap|date=March 2020|reason=Who are \"them\"?}}. Dasch died in 1992 at the age of 89 in [[Ludwigshafen]], [[Germany]]. Burger died in 1975.\n\nSometime in the 1960s or 1970s, the [[National Socialist White People's Party]] placed an unauthorized monument to the executed spies in a thicket in southwest Washington, D.C. on National Park Service land. It went largely unknown and ignored for several decades; the Park Service removed it in 2010.<ref name=\"wapomonument\">{{cite news |last=Cox |first=John Woodrow |date=June 23, 2017 |title=Six Nazi spies were executed in D.C. White supremacists gave them a memorial \u2014 on federal land. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/retropolis/wp/2017/06/23/six-nazi-spies-were-executed-in-d-c-white-supremacists-gave-them-a-memorial-on-federal-land/ |work=The Washington Post |access-date=June 23, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Duquesne Spy Ring]]\n*''[[They Came to Blow Up America]]'', a 1943 film based on Operation Pastorius, starring [[George Sanders]]\n*''[[Saboteur (film)|Saboteur]]'', a 1942 film revolving around acts of sabotage on the US mainland during World War II.\n*[[New York at War]], military parade held at same time\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n;Bibliography\n{{external media | width = 210px | align = right | headerimage= | video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?181143-1/saboteurs-nazi-raid-america ''Booknotes'' interview with Michael Dobbs on ''Saboteurs: The Nazi Raid on America'', 28 March 2004], [[C-SPAN]]}}\n*Dobbs, Michael, ''Saboteurs: The Nazi Raid on America,'' New York: Knopf, 2004. {{ISBN|0-375-41470-3}}\n*Rachlis, Eugene, ''They Came to Kill: The Story of Eight Nazi Saboteurs in America'', New York: Random House, 1961.\n*[[Joseph E. Persico|Persico, Joseph E.]], ''Roosevelt's Secret War: FDR and World War II Espionage'', New York:Random House, 2001, pp.&nbsp;199\u2013205. {{ISBN|0-375-50246-7}}\n*[https://www.fbi.gov/libref/historic/famcases/nazi/nazi.htm Federal Bureau of Investigation: George John Dasch and the Nazi Saboteurs]\n*[http://www.usswashington.com/dl10ju42.htm Lippmann, David H., ''World War II Plus 55, June 10-13th, 1942'']\n*[http://www.montauklife.com/history/history_night_of_the_nazis.html Montauk Life: The Night of the Nazis]\n*[https://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/html/historics/USSC_CR_0317_0001_ZS.html Cornell University School of Law: ''Ex Parte Quirin'' (summary)]\n*Samaha, Joel, ''et al.'' (eds.), ''Transcript of Proceedings before the Military Commission to Try Persons Charged with Offenses against the Law of War and the Articles of War, Washington D.C., 8 to 31 July 1942'', Minneapolis: University of Minnesota, 2004. [http://www.soc.umn.edu/~samaha/nazi_saboteurs/indexnazi.htm]\n*Abella, Alex & Gordon, Scott, ''Shadow Enemies: Hitler's Secret Terrorist Plot Against the United States'', Guilford, CT: Lyons Press, 2002. {{ISBN|1-58574-722-X}}\n\n'''Further information'''\n*[http://www.thisamericanlife.org/Radio_Episode.aspx?sched=1019 The Facts Don't Matter] An hour-long ''This American Life'' radio episode (original air date 3/12/2004) about the events leading up to ''Ex parte Quirin''\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Operation Pastorius}}\n*[http://ghostsofdc.org/2012/02/09/six-nazi-saboteurs-executed-in-washington/ Six Nazi  Saboteurs Executed in Washington] - Ghosts of DC history blog\n*{{IMDb title|id=0036426 |title= They Came to Blow Up America}} - a 1943 film about saboteurs, led by a German-American, landing on Long Island\n*{{cite newspaper |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/03/nyregion/john-cullen-coast-guardsman-who-detected-spies-dies-at-90.html |title= John Cullen, Coast Guardsman Who Detected Spies, Dies at 90 |author= Richard Goldstein |date= September 2, 2011 |work= The New York Times}}\n\n[[Category:1942 in the United States]]\n[[Category:World War II espionage]]\n[[Category:Economic warfare]]\n[[Category:United States military law]]\n[[Category:Abwehr operations]]\n[[Category:Military operations of World War II involving Germany|Pastorius]]\n[[Category:American Theater of World War II]]\n[[Category:1942 in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:1942 in Florida]]\n[[Category:1942 in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Germany\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:June 1942 events]]\n", "name_user": "Rontrigger", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMission", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operation_Pastorius"}
{"title_page": "Green Mountain Arena", "text_new": "{{Infobox venue|\n stadium_name = Green Mountain Arena|\n nickname = |\n image = |\n location = 704 Bridge Street [[Morrisville, Vermont]] 05661|\n broke_ground = |\n opened = |\n capacity = 1,000|\n owner = |\n operator = |\n surface = |\n construction_cost = |\n former_names = |\n architect = |\n tenants = [[Peoples Academy High School|Peoples Academy Wolves]] ([[Vermont Principals Association|VPA]])<br>[[Vermont Wild]] ([[Federal Hockey League|FHL]]) (2011)|\n seating_capicity = 1,000|\n}}\n\nThe '''Green Mountain Arena''' is a 1,000-seat multi-purpose [[arena]] in [[Morrisville, Vermont|Morrisville]], [[Vermont]].  It is home to the [[Peoples Academy High School]] Wolves varsity hockey team.  In the fall of 2011, it was home to the short lived [[Vermont Wild]] of the [[Federal Hockey League]].\n\n==External links==\n*[http://greenmountainarenavt.com/ Green Mountain Arena official website]\n\n{{Coord|44|34|4|N|72|36|34|W|type:landmark_scale:1000|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Indoor arenas in Vermont]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Vermont]]\n[[Category:Indoor ice hockey venues in the United States]]\n\n\n{{Vermont-sports-venue-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Stadium|\n stadium_name = Green Mountain Arena|\n nickname = |\n image = |\n location = 704 Bridge Street [[Morrisville, Vermont]] 05661|\n broke_ground = |\n opened = |\n capacity = 1,000|\n owner = |\n operator = |\n surface = |\n construction_cost = |\n former_names = |\n architect = |\n tenants = [[Peoples Academy High School|Peoples Academy Wolves]] ([[Vermont Principals Association|VPA]])<br>[[Vermont Wild]] ([[Federal Hockey League|FHL]]) (2011)|\n seating_capicity = 1,000|\n}}\n\nThe '''Green Mountain Arena''' is a 1,000-seat multi-purpose [[arena]] in [[Morrisville, Vermont|Morrisville]], [[Vermont]].  It is home to the [[Peoples Academy High School]] Wolves varsity hockey team.  In the fall of 2011, it was home to the short lived [[Vermont Wild]] of the [[Federal Hockey League]].\n\n==External links==\n*[http://greenmountainarenavt.com/ Green Mountain Arena official website]\n\n{{Coord|44|34|4|N|72|36|34|W|type:landmark_scale:1000|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Indoor arenas in Vermont]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Vermont]]\n[[Category:Indoor ice hockey venues in the United States]]\n\n{{Vermont-sports-venue-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Green_Mountain_Arena"}
{"title_page": "Celebrity (album)", "text_new": "{{short description|2001 studio album by NSYNC}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Celebrity\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[*NSYNC]]\n| cover        = Celebrity cover.png\n| border       = yes\n| alt          = NSYNC walking down a red carpet, surrounded by flashing cameras and excited people staring at them.\n| released     = {{start date|2001|07|24}}\n| recorded     = 2001\n| venue        = \n| studio       = {{Collapsible list|title={{nobold|Various}}|Backroom ([[Glendale, California]], U.S.)|Battery (New York City, U.S.)|Carpal Tunnel (Los Angeles, U.S.)|Clinton (New York City, U.S.)|[[Larrabee Sound Studios|Larrabee North]] ([[Universal City, California]], U.S.)|Location (Stockholm, Sweden)|[[Metalworks Studios|Metalworks]] (Toronto, Canada)|Parc (Orlando, Florida, U.S.)|[[Record Plant]] (Los Angeles, U.S.)|[[MSR Studios|Right Track]] (New York City, U.S.)|Sound Chamber ([[North Hollywood, Los Angeles]], U.S.)|[[Westlake Recording Studios|Westlake]] (Los Angeles, U.S.)|Wire (Orlando, Florida, U.S.)}}\n| genre        =\n*[[Pop rock]]<ref name=\"credits\"/><ref name=\"EW\"/> \n*[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref name=\"SlantMagazine\"/>\n*[[electronica]]<ref name=\"SlantMagazine\"/>\n\n| length       = {{duration|m=49|s=31}}\n| label        = [[Jive Records|Jive]]\n| producer     = {{hlist|\n*[[BT (musician)|BT]]\n*[[JC Chasez]]\n*[[Rodney Jerkins]]\n*[[Roy \"Royalty\" Hamilton]]\n*[[Kristian Lundin]]\n*[[Brian McKnight]]\n*[[The Neptunes]]\n*[[PAJAM]]\n*[[Rami Yacoub]]\n*Riprock 'n' Alex G\n*[[Wade Robson|Wade J. Robson]]\n*Jake Schulze\n*[[Justin Timberlake]]\n*Robin Wiley\n}}\n| prev_title   = [[No Strings Attached (NSYNC album)|No Strings Attached]]\n| prev_year    = 2000\n| next_title   = [[Greatest Hits (NSYNC album)|Greatest Hits]]\n| next_year    = 2005\n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = Celebrity\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Pop (song)|Pop]]\n | single1date = May 14, 2001\n | single2     = [[Gone (NSYNC song)|Gone]]\n | single2date = September 4, 2001\n | single3     = [[Girlfriend (NSYNC song)|Girlfriend]]\n | single3date = March 12, 2002\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Celebrity''''' is the third and final studio album by American boy band [[NSYNC]], released on July 24, 2001, by [[Jive Records]]. Due to constant criticism from critics about not being a \"credible group\" in contrast to other established music acts, as well as expectations to beat their [[No Strings Attached (NSYNC album)|previous album's]] first week sales of 2.4 million copies, NSYNC began experimenting with different sounds for the album, such as [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[electronica]], [[2-step garage|two-step]], and [[new jack swing]]. Similar to ''No Strings Attached'', a wide range of producers contributed to the album, including [[BT (musician)|BT]], [[Rodney Jerkins]], [[Brian McKnight]], [[PAJAM]], and [[The Neptunes]]. [[Justin Timberlake]] and [[JC Chasez]] were also more hands-on with production, co-writing ten of thirteen tracks, in an effort to find the album's unique tone.\n\nAfter suffering from two delays due to unfinished recording sessions, ''Celebrity'' was released to generally positive reception by critics. The album was the band's second to debut at number-one on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], with first-week sales of 1,879,495 copies, the second best debut-week sales in the country at the time until the release of [[Adele]]'s ''[[25 (Adele album)|25]]'' in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|title=Adele's '25' Is the 20th Album to Sell a Million Copies in a Week: See the Full List|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6770482/adele-25-other-million-selling-albums|website=Billboard|access-date=January 5, 2016}}</ref> They embarked on two tours to promote the album's release; [[PopOdyssey]] and the [[Celebrity Tour]]. Initially, the release date of ''Celebrity'' was meant to coincide with PopOdyssey, however, constant delays meant that NSYNC performed the majority of the songs on tour before the album was released.\n\n==Background==\nAt the 2000 [[Billboard Music Award|''Billboard'' Music Awards]] on December 5, NSYNC announced that they would begin \"experimenting with new music\" for their third studio album in January\u2013February 2001, at a recording studio in Florida.<ref name=\"MTVStudio\"/> [[Justin Timberlake]] revealed that they planned to spend two months there to come up with ideas, while [[Joey Fatone]] stated that the group may leave the state as the album progresses. NSYNC revealed that they wanted to work with [[Kevin \"She'kspere\" Briggs]] and [[Richard Marx]], who they had collaborated with on their second studio album, ''[[No Strings Attached (NSYNC album)|No Strings Attached]]''.<ref name=\"MTVStudio\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1375008/nsync-to-hit-studio-in-january/|title= 'NSYNC to Hit Studio in January|first=Teri|last=Vanhorn|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=December 7, 2000|access-date=February 15, 2016}}</ref>\n{{multiple image|align=right\n|total_width=250\n|image1=JC Chasez (cropped).jpg\n|image2=Justin Timberlake - Justified World Tour - Earls Court - 6 (cropped).jpg\n|footer=[[JC Chasez]] and [[Justin Timberlake]] co-wrote ten of thirteen songs on the album and produced the majority of the tracklist in an effort to experiment with different sounds and genres.<ref name=\"MTVSeek\"/>\n}}\nAlthough ''No Strings Attached'' sold 14 million copies worldwide, including 2.4 million in the US during its opening week, the group were constantly ridiculed by critics, as they did not fit their preconceptions as a \"credible group\" and weren't considered \"artistic\".<ref name=\"CelebrityBillboard\"/><ref name=\"RSPop\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/n-sync-true-tales-of-the-pop-life-236982/|title='N Sync: True Tales of the Pop Life|author=Tour\u00e9|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=August 16, 2001|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> In response, they decided to be more involved in production, co-writing ten of the album's thirteen tracks. [[JC Chasez]] discussed the album's recording process in an interview with ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'':<ref name=\"CelebrityBillboard\"/><blockquote>Our objective was not to be self-conscious and try to make another hit record. Instead, we set out to make a record that was more reflective of what turns us on musically. We also wanted to prove that pop music comes in a lot of different flavors. It's not all [[Bubblegum pop|bubble-gum]].</blockquote> The band decided to assign roles for each member, in order to combat media perception of \"leadership roles within the group\".<ref name=\"RSPop\"/> Timberlake and Chasez concentrated on the album's production and compositions, [[Lance Bass]] was assigned to handle business and management, while Fatone and [[Chris Kirkpatrick]] decided to implement their ideas into their tour.<ref name=\"RSPop\"/>\n\nNSYNC sought out several collaborators in order to add new styles to their sound, such as [[BT (musician)|BT]] and [[The Neptunes]].<ref name=\"MTVSeek\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1445474/nsync-seek-to-impress-with-skills-not-sales/|title='NSYNC Seek To Impress With Skills, Not Sales|last=Vanhorn|first=Teri|website=[[MTV News]]|date=July 27, 2001|access-date=February 5, 2020}}</ref> BT was initially hesitant to work with the group when Timberlake approached him in the fall of 2000, as their styles were opposite from each other. He finally agreed when Timberlake was willing to work with the sound used in \"The Hip Hop Phenomenon\", taken from the UK version of his 1999 album ''[[Movement in Still Life]]'', stating \"If you wanna do something that [[Punk rock|punk-rock]], I'll do it\".<ref name=\"MTVSeek\"/><ref name=\"BT\"/> During production, BT used special equipment usually used in movie sound effects, and constantly yelled out [[Michael Jackson]]'s name towards Timberlake.<ref name=\"BT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1444712/bt-earns-king-of-dirty-pop-title-with-nsync-britney-tracks/|title=BT Earns 'King Of Dirty Pop' Title With 'NSYNC, Britney Tracks|last=Moss|first=Corey|website=[[MTV News]]|date=June 22, 2001|access-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref> He wanted to ensure that the song transitioned from \"[[Contemporary R&B|new-school R&B]], [[Timbaland]]-style beats, to [[progressive house]]\".<ref name=\"BT\"/>\n\nThe album's second single \"[[Gone (NSYNC song)|Gone]]\" was initially written as a duet between Timberlake and Michael Jackson, but was declined by the latter.<ref name=\"GoneUpcoming\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6084534/justin-timberlake-duet-michael-jackson-gone-oprah|title=Justin Timberlake Nearly Had Duet With Michael Jackson a Decade Ago|last=Payne|first=Chris|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=May 8, 2014|access-date=February 15, 2020}}</ref> Timberlake brought the song up to the band's A&R team, where it was eventually recorded by the group. Jackson changed his mind after the song's release and wanted it to only be performed as a duet with Timberlake. However, they could not find a way to revamp the song.<ref name=\"GoneBillboard\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/6084699/n-sync-gone-michael-jackson-duet-justin-timberlake|title='N Sync's 'Gone' Comes Back: Why Michael Jackson's Proposed Duet is an Essential Justin Timberlake Track|last=Lipshutz|first=Jason|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=May 9, 2014|access-date=February 15, 2020}}</ref> Timberlake was also determined to get [[Stevie Wonder]] to play the harmonica for \"Something Like You\" after he came up with the composition alongside co-writer Robin Wiley. Wonder recorded the part when [[Jive Records]] contacted him, which Timberlake described as a \"surreal moment\".<ref name=\"MTVSeek\"/>\n\n==Composition and lyrical content==\nThe album's first track \"[[Pop (song)|Pop]]\" refers to the band's longevity during a period of [[celebrity culture]].<ref name=\"Folks\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theyoungfolks.com/music/83499/from-the-record-crate-nsync-celebrity-2001/|title=From the Record Crate: *NSYNC \u2013 Celebrity (2001)|last=Lockhart|first=Bri|website=The Young Folks|date=July 24, 2016|access-date=October 17, 2019}}</ref> Larry Flick of ''Billboard'' described the song as \"a crafty, anthemic blend of [[Cameo (band)|Cameo-style]] [[Electro (music)|electro-funk]] beats, [[Europop|Euro-pop]] synths, heavy-metal guitars, and Timberlake's now-signature human beat-box riffs\", while John Hugar of [[Uproxx]] described the song as \"a sort of proto-salvo against in the [[Rockism and poptimism|rockist vs. poptimists argument]]\", and stated that it was a preview to \"[[Rock Your Body]]\".<ref name=\"Uproxx\">{{cite web|url=https://uproxx.com/music/nsync-celebrity-15th-anniversary/|title=NSYNC\u2019s \u2018Celebrity\u2019 Signaled Their Imminent Demise|last=Hugar|first=John|website=[[Uproxx]]|date=July 24, 2016|access-date=October 17, 2019}}</ref> The next track \"Celebrity\" is lyrically themed around the band's struggle of being accepted in celebrity culture without being manipulated.<ref name=\"Folks\"/> The song was produced by [[Rodney Jerkins]].<ref name=\"Fuse\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fuse.tv/2016/07/nsync-celebrity-15th-anniversary-review-best-songs|title=*NSYNC'S 'Celebrity' Anniversary: Ranking Every Song 15 Years Later|last=Gracie|first=Bianca|website=[[Fuse (TV channel)|Fuse]]|date=July 26, 2016|access-date=October 17, 2019}}</ref> \"The Game is Over\", a track utilizing \"arcade noises and video game beeps\", was described by Flick as a \"safe-single bet\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/00s/2001/BB-2001-07-28.pdf|title=Spotlights|last=Flick|first=Larry|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=July 28, 2001|volume=113|issue=30|page=22|format=PDF|access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref> The fourth track \"[[Girlfriend (NSYNC song)|Girlfriend]]\" is an [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] song produced by [[The Neptunes]].<ref name=\"Fuse\"/> The remix, which featured [[rapper]] [[Nelly]], gave the song \"a distinct hip hop feel\".<ref name=\"Folks\"/> \"The Two of Us\" contains a \"British dancefloor beat\",<ref name=\"BillboardRelease\"/> while the sixth track \"[[Gone (NSYNC song)|Gone]]\" was described by ''Billboard'' staff as being \"harrowing, relentless and unmistakably final\".<ref>{{cite magazine|date=April 23, 2018|title=The 100 Greatest Boy Band Songs of All Time: Critics' Picks|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/list/8362499/greatest-boy-band-songs-of-all-time-top-100|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=April 28, 2018}}</ref> The [[Sentimental ballad|ballad]] was also noted by Hugar as the precursor to \u201c[[Cry Me a River (Justin Timberlake song)|Cry Me a River]]\".<ref name=\"Uproxx\"/>\n\nThe seventh track \"Tell Me, Tell Me... Baby\" was written by [[Max Martin]], and contains elements of Europop.<ref name=\"ErlewineAllRev\"/> \"Up Against the Wall\" is an R&B song with genres of [[new jack swing]] and [[2-step garage|two-step]].<ref name=\"BillboardRelease\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/00s/2001/BB-2001-07-21.pdf|title=DB Beat - Mixes Gentler Drum 'N' Bass On Breakbeat Science - Choice Cuts|last=Paoletta|first=Michael|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=July 21, 2001|volume=113|issue=29|page=48|format=PDF|access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref> \"See Right Through You\" is the ninth track in the album, and also contains an R&B sound.<ref name=\"Fuse\"/> The song describes a \"tale of betrayal by scheming girls.\"<ref name=\"EW\"/> The [[Brian McKnight]] produced \"Selfish\" combined the vocals of Chasez and Timberlake with an [[Adult contemporary music|adult contemporary]] track.<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite website|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2001/07/27/n-sync-celebrity|title=''Celebrity''|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=July 27, 2001|accessdate=July 15, 2012|last=Browne|first=David|authorlink=David Browne (journalist)|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905142028/http://ew.com/article/2001/07/27/n-sync-celebrity/|archivedate=September 5, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> \"Just Don't Tell Me That\" is a [[teen pop]] track similarly compared to songs by [[Britney Spears]] and the [[Backstreet Boys]].<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite website|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/celebrity-20010709|title=''Celebrity''|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=July 9, 2001|accessdate=July 15, 2012|last=Walters|first=Barry}}</ref> The twelfth track \"Something Like You\" is a ballad likened to the discography of [[98 Degrees]], with [[Stevie Wonder]] playing the [[harmonica]].<ref name=\"EW\"/> The thirteenth and final track in the US album \"Do Your Thing\" is described by [[David Browne (journalist)|David Browne]] as \"mild [[electronica]]\",<ref name=\"EW\"/> and was included since Jive Records wanted a song that showcased the group's vocal talents and harmony.<ref name=\"MTVSeek\"/>\n\n==Promotion==\n[[File:TRL studios in Times Square in 2006.jpg|thumb|right|The band appeared on an episode of ''[[Total Request Live|TRL]]'' on the album's release date.]]\nOn May 11, 2001, [[MTV]] played a recording of \"Pop\" via satellite during NSYNC's tour rehearsal for [[PopOdyssey]], which led the song to be released to radio three days later.<ref name=\"CelebrityBillboard\"/> Initially, ''Celebrity'' was supposed to be released in May, coinciding with the start of the tour. However, the album was pushed back to June 26, as the band were still in the process of recording.<ref name=\"ynewsA\">{{cite web|url=http://music.yahoo.com/read/news/12038403|title='N Sync's 'Celebrity' Scheduled For June 26 Release |date=April 3, 2001|accessdate=January 9, 2009|last=Gelman|first=Jason|work=[[Yahoo! Music]]|archivedate=September 11, 2011|archiveurl=http://www.freezepage.com/1315706229ECAYSTSYML?url=http://new.music.yahoo.com/nsync/news/artist-name-n-sync-id-1033340-s-celebrity-scheduled-for-june-26-release--12038403}}</ref> As the tour needed to conclude prior to the start of the [[2001 NFL season]], the album was again pushed back to July 24, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1443496/nsync-push-back-tour-album-release/|title='NSYNC Push Back Tour, Album Release|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|website=[[MTV News]]|date=May 9, 2001|access-date=February 5, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Yahoo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1444687/20010621/n_sync.jhtml|title='NSYNC's Celebrity: More Songs About Young Love|date=2001-06-21|accessdate=2009-01-09|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|work=[[MTV News]]|archivedate=11 September 2011|archiveurl=http://www.freezepage.com/1315706713HXECWPSIKH?url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1444687/nsyncs-upcoming-love-songs.jhtml}}</ref> Consequently, the band decided to perform the album's new songs on tour before release.<ref name=\"Yahoo\"/> The tour was sponsored by [[Verizon Communications|Verizon]], who launched several television and radio advertising campaigns promoting its release date.<ref name=\"Opening\"/> In an interview with ''Billboard'', Chasez stated that the concept of playing new songs in a concert was \"unusual\", but felt that it was a \"good sign\" that the crowd were actively participating.<ref name=\"CelebrityBillboard\"/> Jive Records president [[Barry Weiss]] was also taken aback by the band's touring approach, acknowledging that the audience response would indicate \"an album of immeasurable creative and commercial depth\".<ref name=\"CelebrityBillboard\"/>\n\nA television special titled ''The Road to Celebrity'' was broadcast on MTV from July 21\u201322, 2001.<ref name=\"CelebrityBillboard\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/billboard/feature/exclusive/nsync1.jsp|title='N Sync: Shouldering The Burden of ''Celebrity''|accessdate=February 15, 2016|last=Flick |first=Larry|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|archivedate=June 30, 2001|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010630235832/http://www.billboard.com/billboard/feature/exclusive/nsync1.jsp|url-status=dead}}</ref> The album premiere was held at [[West Hollywood, California|West Hollywood]] on July 23, 2001, which included celebrities such as [[Hugh Hefner]] and the [[Mary-Kate and Ashley Olsen|Olsen Twins]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1445371/nsync-party-with-britney-bt-and-hugh-hefner-at-celebrity-soiree/|title='NSYNC Party With Britney, BT And Hugh Hefner At Celebrity Soiree|last=Boone|first=Christian|website=[[MTV News]]|date=July 24, 2001|access-date=February 5, 2020}}</ref> The band also played several songs at a [[tailgate party]] in the parking lot and appeared on ''[[Total Request Live|TRL]]'' on July 24, 2001, which coincided with the album's release.<ref name=\"CelebrityBillboard\"/>\n\n===Tours===\n{{See also|PopOdyssey|Celebrity Tour}}\nThe band embarked on two concert tours to promote the album. The first was PopOdyssey, which began on May 23, 2001 at the [[TIAA Bank Field|Alltel Stadium]] in [[Jacksonville, Florida]], and concluded on September 1, 2001 in [[Mexico City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2001/05/30/n-sync-finally-hit-road/|title='N Sync finally hit the road|last=Susman|first=Gary|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=May 30, 2001|access-date=October 17, 2019}}</ref> Earning over $90&nbsp;million, it was one of the biggest tours of 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1451603/20011221/u2.jhtml|title=U2, 'NSYNC, Backstreet Top List of 2001's Biggest Concert Grossers|date=December 21, 2001|accessdate=January 9, 2009|last=Wiederhorn|first=Jon|publisher=[[MTV News]]|archivedate=September 11, 2011|archiveurl=http://www.freezepage.com/1315705054CAFFQJRGTK?url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1451603/u2-top-list-2001s-biggest-concert-grossers.jhtml}}</ref> The second was the [[Celebrity Tour]], which began on March 3, 2002 in [[Portland, Oregon]] and concluded on April 28, 2002 in [[Orlando, Florida]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.yahoo.com/read/news/12056871|title=*NSYNC Embarking On 'Celebrity' Tour With A Twist |date=2002-02-19|accessdate=2009-01-09|last=Baker|first=Soren|work=Yahoo! Music|archivedate=11 September 2011|archiveurl=http://www.freezepage.com/1315708217GZCBNHZOGX?url=http://new.music.yahoo.com/nsync/news/artist-name-nsync-id-1033340-embarking-on-celebrity-tour-with-a-twist--12056871}}</ref> In contrast to PopOdyssey, the tour favored music over spectacle, which incorporated their older songs with new arrangements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/ae/music/article/Oh-boys-On-a-Celebrity-high-N-Sync-journeys-1081812.php|title=Oh boys! On a 'Celebrity' high, N' Sync journeys to Tacoma|last=Stout|first=Gene|date=February 28, 2002|website=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]|access-date=September 14, 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61gj1TRvZ?url=http://www.seattlepi.com/ae/music/article/Oh-boys-On-a-Celebrity-high-N-Sync-journeys-1081812.php|archive-date=September 14, 2011}}</ref> It earned nearly $30&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1459239/20021220/spears_britney.jhtml|title=Britney, 'NSYNC Buried in Ticket Sales By McCartney, Stones|date=December 20, 2001|accessdate=January 9, 2009|last=Wiederhorn|first=Jon|publisher=[[MTV News]]|archivedate=September 11, 2011|archiveurl=http://www.freezepage.com/1315705587SKSJHOQORG?url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1459239/mccartney-tops-tour-receipts.jhtml}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 65/100<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/celebrity/nsync |title=Reviews for ''Celebrity'' by *NSYNC |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=July 15, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"ErlewineAllRev\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/celebrity-mw0000003721 |title=''Celebrity'' \u2013 *NSYNC |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=August 28, 2011 |last=Erlewine |first=Stephen Thomas |authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n| rev2Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Blender\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.blender.com:80/reviews/review_1106.html |title=N Sync: ''Celebrity'' |work=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]] |issue=2 |date=August\u2013September 2001 |accessdate=August 28, 2011 |last=Considine |first=J. D. |authorlink=J. D. Considine |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040818032108/http://www.blender.com/reviews/review_1106.html |archivedate=August 18, 2004 |page=126 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Robert Christgau#Consumer Guide|Christgau's Consumer Guide]]''\n| rev3Score = {{rating-Christgau|hm1}}<ref name=\"ConsumerGuide\">{{cite web |url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_album.php?id=10146 |title='N Sync: ''Celebrity'' |publisher=RobertChristgau.com |accessdate=July 15, 2012 |last=Christgau |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Christgau}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev4Score = B<ref name=\"EW\"/>\n| rev5 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev5Score = 8/10<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.nme.com/reviews//5525 |title=*NSYNC : ''Celebrity'' |work=[[NME]] |date=July 31, 2001 |accessdate=July 15, 2012 |last=Needham |first=Alex |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304101615/http://www.nme.com/reviews//5525 |archivedate=March 4, 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev6Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |title='N Sync: ''Celebrity'' |work=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |issue=181 |date=September 2001 |page=114}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev7Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\"/>\n| rev8 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite book |chapter='N Sync |last=Sinagra |first=Laura |title=[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]] |editor-last1=Brackett |editor-first1=Nathan |editor-last2=Hoard |editor-first2=Christian |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |edition=4th |year=2004 |location=New York |pages=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/592 592\u201393] |isbn=0-7432-0169-8 }}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Slant Magazine]]''\n| rev9Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"SlantMagazine\">{{cite web |url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/nsync-celebrity |title=*Nsync: ''Celebrity'' |work=[[Slant Magazine]] |date=July 22, 2001 |accessdate=July 28, 2015 |last=Cinquemani |first=Sal}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Celebrity'' received generally positive reviews from contemporary music critics. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album received an [[Weighted mean|average]] score of 65 based on 11 reviews.<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/>\n\nUpon the album's release, ''[[AllMusic]]'' senior editor [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] wrote that ''Celebrity'' is NSYNC's \"most varied album yet, but the emergence of Timberlake and Chasez as credible soulful singers and, yes, songwriters makes it their best album yet, and one of the best of the teen pop boom of 1999\u20132001\".<ref name=\"ErlewineAllRev\"/> J.D. Considine of ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]'' felt that the album \"shines brightest when the group matures enough to forget about its image and focus on the tunes\", stating that songs such as \"Up Against the Wall\" and \"Celebrity\" aren't as satisfying as the gently melodic \"Something Like You.\"<ref name=\"Blender\"/> In ''[[Robert Christgau#Consumer Guide|Christgau's Consumer Guide]]'', [[Robert Christgau]] gave the album a one-star honorable mention, writing that \"they survive writing their own songs\", giving examples of \"Selfish\" and \"Do Your Thing\".<ref name=\"ConsumerGuide\"/> David Browne of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' stated that the album was \"the consummate teen-pop experience\", praising their diversification of genres ranging from R&B, ballads, self-expression and Europop.<ref name=\"EW\"/>\n\nAlex Needham of ''[[NME]]'' gave the album an 8/10 score, writing that although NSYNC shows discontent in the album, they \"have the tunes to make up for it\".<ref name=\"NME\"/> In a review from ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', Barry Walters highlighted how the anxiety in their vocals have allowed them to \"pave a new high road for teen pop\u2019s future\".<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\"/> Writing for ''[[Slant Magazine|Slant]]'', Sal Cinquemani criticized the album's experimental approach, writing that it was \"unfortunate that the group couldn\u2019t completely discard the classic hit-making formula in favor of the more experimental pop that seems so inherent in this and their last album, ''No Strings Attached''.\" However, he was optimistic that the band could become \"[[The Beatles]] of their generation\" if they survive the growing pains and their aging demographic.<ref name=\"SlantMagazine\"/>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nIn the United States, ''Celebrity'' debuted at number one on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]. Although it did not sell as much as its predecessor, ''No Strings Attached'', ''Celebrity'' still managed to gain the second-best debut week sales at the time since SoundScan began monitoring record retailers in 1991, selling 1,879,955 copies.<ref name=\"Opening\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/00s/2001/BB-2001-08-11.pdf|title=U.S. Retailers Relish 'Celebrity'|author=Billboard Staff|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=August 11, 2001|volume=113|issue=32|page=5|format=PDF|access-date=February 12, 2020}}</ref> It was suggested by ''Billboard'' that the album's failure to match the first week sales of their previous album was due to the US economy's weaker state in comparison to the previous year, as well as the music industry's first decline in album sales in more than a decade.<ref name=\"Opening\"/> The album debuted at number one in Canada by selling 71,254 copies, which was the biggest first week album to date that year.<ref name=\"Opening\"/> ''Celebrity'' sold 20,000 units in Japan's first week sales, alongside the 13,000 units sold in the UK's first week.<ref name=\"Opening\"/> Several European companies reported that album sales were slow, including [[Fnac]] in France and Spain, ''[[WOM magazin|WOM]]'' in Germany, and [[Casa Ricordi|Ricordi]] in Italy.<ref name=\"Opening\"/>\n\nOn August 22, 2001, the album was certified five-times platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA), denoting five million shipments.<ref name=\"RIAA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=Celebrity#search_section|title=Gold & Platinum - RIAA|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|access-date=February 15, 2020}}</ref> It ended up becoming the third best-selling album in 2001, selling 4.42 million copies.<ref name=\"MTVSales\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1451664/got-charts-linkin-park-shaggy-nsync-are-2001s-top-sellers/|title=Got Charts? Linkin Park, Shaggy, 'NSYNC Are 2001's Top-Sellers|last=Basham|first=David|website=[[MTV News]]|date=January 4, 2002|access-date=February 15, 2020}}</ref> Sales of the album were marginally lower than [[Shaggy (musician)|Shaggy's]] ''[[Hot Shot (Shaggy album)|Hot Shot]]'' by 86,000 copies, which only beat their album in the [[cassette tape|cassette]] format; ''Hot Shot'' sold 304,000 tapes, while ''Celebrity'' only sold 92,000 tapes in comparison.<ref name=\"MTVSales\"/> ''Celebrity'' was ranked at number nine on the ''Billboard'' 200 year-end chart in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top Billboard 200 Albums - Year-End - 2001|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2001/top-billboard-200-albums|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 2015, the album sold 5,002,000 copies in the US according to [[Nielsen SoundScan|Nielsen Music]].<ref name=billboard2015/> It sold an additional 826,000 units at the BMG Music Club as of February 2003.<ref name=\"BMG\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn a retrospective article in 2016, John Hugar of Uproxx stated that ''Celebrity'' felt \"like a logical swan song as well as a transitional album\", as the album came after their previous album ''No Strings Attached'' achieved record-breaking commercial success, which made clear that \"[the] band had beat out all of their contemporaries\u2014even Backstreet Boys [...] ''Celebrity'' was acknowledging [with the title] exactly how huge they were, and how many people were waiting with baited breath for their next move\".<ref name=\"Uproxx\"/> Although it did not achieve a debut on par with its predecessor, the album \"had enough memorable singles to guarantee they would stay in the spotlight,\" while a break-up was imminent \"[to] allow the band's most talented and charismatic member to take his place as pop icon\", referring to Timberlake's future solo career. Hugar compared it to [[Zayn Malik]] and [[Harry Styles]]' aspirations to pursue solo stardom after [[One Direction]]'s announced hiatus, mentioning that it is \"a reminder that boy bands are rarely built to last\".<ref name=\"Uproxx\"/>\n\nFor the album's 15th anniversary in 2016, Bianca Gracie of [[Fuse (TV channel)|Fuse]] acknowledged that following the release, \"it was clear a hiatus was imminent, as Justin Timberlake surpassed JC Chasez as the lead singer and began to take more creative control, co-writing and co-producing many tracks on the LP,\" while \"the timeless nature of \"Gone\" proves just why JT went on to be a major solo artist\".<ref name=\"Fuse\"/> Similarly, [[NPR]]'s Maria Sherman stated the album \"leaned even harder into R&B\" and \"firmly established Timberlake as the bandleader\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/20/818464377/nsync-no-strings-attached-20th-anniversary-timberlake-backstreet|title=The Future According To NSYNC: 20 Years Of 'No Strings Attached'|last=Sherman|first=Maria|website=[[NPR]]|date=March 20, 2020|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nCredits adapted from the album's [[liner notes]].<ref name=\"LinerNotes\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=Celebrity|others=[[NSYNC]]|year=2001|type=booklet|publisher=[[Jive Records]] |id=01241-41758-2|location=New York City}}</ref> All lead vocals provided by [[Justin Timberlake]] and [[JC Chasez]].\n{{Track listing\n| headline = ''Celebrity'' {{nobold|\u2014 American and Canadian edition}}<ref name=\"LinerNotes\"/>\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length = 49:31\n\n| title1 = [[Pop (song)|Pop]]\n| writer1 = {{flat list|\n*[[Justin Timberlake]]\n*[[Wade Robson|Wade J. Robson]]\n}}\n| extra1 = {{flat list|\n*[[BT (musician)|BT]]\n*Timberlake\n*Robson\n}}\n| length1 = 3:57\n\n| title2 = Celebrity\n| writer2 = {{flat list|\n*Timberlake\n*Robson\n*[[J. Valentine]]\n}}\n| extra2 = {{flat list|\n*[[Rodney Jerkins]]\n*Timberlake\n*Robson\n}}\n| length2 = 3:17\n\n| title3 = The Game Is Over\n| writer3 = {{flat list|\n*[[JC Chasez]]\n*[[Alex Greggs]]\n*Brad Daymond\n}}\n| extra3 = {{flat list|\n*Riprock 'n' Alex G\n*Chasez\n}}\n| length3 = 3:25\n\n| title4 = [[Girlfriend (NSYNC song)|Girlfriend]]\n| writer4 = {{flat list|\n*Timberlake\n*[[Chad Hugo]]\n*[[Pharrell Williams]]\n}}\n| extra4 = [[The Neptunes]]\n| length4 = 4:13\n\n| title5 = The Two of Us\n| writer5 = {{flat list|\n*Chasez\n*Greggs\n*Daymond\n}}\n| extra5 = {{flat list|\n*Riprock 'n' Alex G\n*Chasez\n}}\n| length5 = 3:50\n\n| title6 = [[Gone (NSYNC song)|Gone]]\n| writer6 = {{flat list|\n*Timberlake\n*Robson\n}}\n| extra6 = {{flat list|\n*Timberlake\n*Robson\n}}\n| length6 = 4:51\n\n| title7 = Tell Me, Tell Me... Baby\n| writer7 = {{flat list|\n*[[Max Martin]]\n*[[Rami Yacoub]]\n}}\n| extra7 = Yacoub\n| length7 = 3:36\n\n| title8 = Up Against the Wall\n| writer8 = {{flat list|\n*Chasez\n*Timberlake\n*Greggs\n*Daymond\n}}\n| extra8 = {{flat list|\n*Riprock 'n' Alex G\n*Chasez\n}}\n| length8 = 3:36\n\n| title9 = See Right Through You\n| writer9 = {{flat list|\n*Timberlake\n*Larry \"Rock\" Campbell\n*Robson\n}}\n| extra9 = {{flat list|\n*Timberlake\n*Robson\n}}\n| length9 = 2:52\n\n| title10 = Selfish\n| writer10 = {{flat list|\n*Chasez\n*Jolyon Skinner\n}}\n| extra10 = [[Brian McKnight]]\n| length10 = 4:19\n\n| title11 = Just Don't Tell Me That\n| writer11 = {{flat list|\n*[[Kristian Lundin]]\n*Jake Schulze\n*[[Andreas Carlsson]]\n}}\n| extra11 = {{flat list|\n*Lundin\n*Schulze\n}}\n| length11 = 3:02\n\n| title12 = Something Like You\n| writer12 = {{flat list|\n*Timberlake\n*[[Robbie Buchanan]]\n*Robin Wiley\n*Jay Landers\n}}\n| extra12 = {{flat list|\n*Timberlake\n*Buchanan\n*Wiley\n}}\n| length12 = 4:14\n\n| title13 = Do Your Thing\n| writer13 = [[J. Moss|James Moss]]\n| extra13 = [[PAJAM]]\n\n| length13 = 4:19\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = ''Celebrity'' {{nobold|\u2014 International edition}}\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length = 52:55\n\n| title13 = That Girl (Will Never Be Mine)\n| note13 = bonus track\n| writer13 = {{flat list|\n*Lundin\n*Schulze\n*Carlsson\n}}\n| extra13 = {{flat list|\n*Lundin\n*Schulze\n}}\n| length13 = 3:24\n\n| title14 = Do Your Thing\n| writer14 = Moss\n| extra14 = PAJAM\n\n| length14 = 4:19\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = ''Celebrity'' {{nobold|\u2014 Australian, British and Japanese edition}}\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length = 56:43\n\n| title13 = That Girl (Will Never Be Mine)\n| note13 = bonus track\n| writer13 = {{flat list|\n*Lundin\n*Schulze\n*Carlsson\n}}\n| extra13 = {{flat list|\n*Lundin\n*Schulze\n}}\n| length13 = 3:24\n\n| title14 = Falling\n| note14 = bonus track\n| writer14 = {{flat list|\n*[[Chris Kirkpatrick]]\n*Bryan Popin\n*Gary Brown\n*Ira Schickman\n}}\n| extra14 = {{flat list|\n*[[Roy \"Royalty\" Hamilton]]\n*Mystery\n}}\n| length14 = 3:48\n\n| title