{"title_page": "Manual Arts High School", "text_new": "{{Infobox school\n|name           = Manual Arts High School\n|native_name    =\n|logo           = \n|image          =MAHS IDENTITY logo.jpg\n|image_size     =230px\n|motto          = '''It Can Be Done'''\n|country        =\n|song           = \n|established    = 1910\n|type           =[[Public school (government funded)|Public]]\n|affiliation    =\n|district       = [[Los Angeles Unified School District]]\n|trustee        = \n|grades         = 9\u201312\n|campus         =\n|chairperson    = \n|president      =\n|principal      =  Erica Thomas-Minor\n|head of school =\n|dean           =\n|custodian      = \n|faculty        =\n|staff          = 72.84 (FTE)<ref name=NCES/>\n|ratio          = 19.33<ref name=NCES/>\n|students       = \n|enrollment     = 1,408 (2017-18)<ref name=NCES>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=0622710&SchoolPageNum=39&ID=062271003163|title=Manual Arts Senior High|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref>\n|athletics      =\n|conference     =Coliseum League<br>[[CIF Los Angeles City Section]]\n|colors         ={{Colorsample|#69359C}}{{Colorsample|#808080}} [[Royal Purple]] and [[Gray]]\n| mascot        = Tommy Toiler\n| mascot image  = \n|team_name      =Toilers\n|location       =4131 South Vermont Avenue<br/>[[Los Angeles, California]] 90037 <br />United States\n|streetaddress  =\n|coordinates    ={{Coord|34.0083|-118.29217|type:edu_region:US-CA|display=inline,title}}\n|website        ={{URL|http://www.mahs.org/}}\n}}\n'''Manual Arts High School''' is a secondary [[Public school (government funded)|public school]] in [[Los Angeles, California]]. When founded, Manual Arts was a vocational high school, but later{{When|date=March 2011}} converted to a traditional curriculum.\n\n==History==\nManual Arts High School was founded in 1910 in the middle of bean fields, one-half mile from the nearest bus stop. It was the third high school in Los Angeles, California after [[Los Angeles High School]] and [[Polytechnic High School (Los Angeles)|L.A. Polytechnic High School]], and is the oldest high school still on its original site in the Los Angeles Unified School District.  The school that would eventually become [[Abraham Lincoln High School (Los Angeles)|Lincoln High]] had been founded decades earlier but was still an elementary school at this time.\n\nOne of the school's first teachers was [[Ethel Percy Andrus]] (1911 - 1915).  In 1916 Dr. Andrus became California's first woman high school principal at Lincoln High School in East Los Angeles.  She later founded [[AARP]].\n\nAfter three semesters in an abandoned grammar school building, Manual Arts High School was opened on Vermont Avenue. After the [[1933 Long Beach earthquake]], the entire campus was rebuilt, constituting the present Manual Arts High School campus adjacent to the [[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]] and [[University of Southern California|USC]]. In 1995, \"The Arts\" became a [[Pacific Bell]] Education First Demonstration Site joining thirteen other demonstration sites in California, and in 1996 the school was named a [[California Distinguished School]]. In 1998, Manual Arts was officially granted [[Digital High School]] status.\n\nThe 2005\u20132006 school year opened with [[small learning communities]] (SLCs), three on each track totaling nine SLCs. Manual Arts was relieved by the opening of [[Santee Education Complex]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laschools.org/project-status/one-project?project_number=55A98010 |title=Project Details |publisher=Laschools.org |date=2011-10-13 |accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref>\n\n===West Adams High School===\nThe school was relieved in 2007 when [[West Adams Preparatory High School]] opened. During the same year, a section of the Manual Arts attendance zone was transferred to [[Belmont High School (Los Angeles)|Belmont High School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laschools.org/project-status/one-project?project_number=55.98021 |title=Project Details |publisher=Laschools.org |date=2011-10-13 |accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2008, the school became part of [[MLA Partner Schools]] through LAUSD's newly created iDesign Schools Division. MLA Partner Schools, in collaboration with West Ed, will operate Manual Arts on a 5-year performance contract approved by the LAUSD School Board.\n\nThe school was expected be relieved by Central Region High School 16 (which became [[Dr. Maya Angelou High School (Los Angeles, California)]]) when that school opened in 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laschools.org/project-status/one-project?project_number=56.40055 |title=Project Details |publisher=Laschools.org |date=2011-10-13 |accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref> and by Augustus Hawkins High School when that school opens in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laschools.org/project-status/one-project?project_number=55.98047 |title=Project Details |publisher=Laschools.org |date=2011-10-13 |accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2011\u20132012 school year, Manual Arts will return to a traditional school calendar schedule.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mahs.org/apps/news/show_news.jsp?REC_ID=180761&id=0 |title=Manual Arts Senior High School |publisher=Mahs.org |date=2011-03-11 |accessdate=2013-10-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004231200/http://www.mahs.org/apps/news/show_news.jsp?REC_ID=180761&id=0 |archivedate=2013-10-04 }}</ref> As a result, several of the school\u2019s small learning communities will be restructured and the number of security on campus will be reduced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-banks-20110517,0,7004032.column |title=Sandy Banks: At Manual Arts High, same goals but different methods|publisher=Latimes.com |date=2011-05-17 |accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref> The  ''''Blewett Football Field''' is named in honor of '''James Blewett''' who was a standout  Manual Arts football player and longtime Head coach with 9 Los Angeles City titles and 225 wins.\n\n==Student body==\nThe racial make-up of the school is mostly Latinos and African-Americans and the neighborhood surrounding the school reflects the same make-up.\n\nDuring the 2004\u20132005 school year, MAHS had 3,766 students,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.lausd.k12.ca.us/cgi-bin/fccgi.exe?w3exec=school.profile.content&which=8743 |title=School Profile (9-12) |publisher=Search.lausd.k12.ca.us |date=2009-09-16 |accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref> including:\n* 3,054 [[Hispanic]]s (81.1%)\n* 701 [[African-Americans]] (18.6%)\n* 5 [[White American]]s (1%)\n* 4 [[Asian American]]s (1%)\n* 2 [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native Americans]] (1%)\n\nAs of 2010, the dropout rate at Manual Arts was 68%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://idea.gseis.ucla.edu/educational-opportunity-report/2011/eor-hs-detail.php?cds_code=19647331935519 |title=UCLA IDEA Educational Opportunity Report |publisher=Idea.gseis.ucla.edu |date= |accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref>\n\nWith more than 90% of students qualifying for free or reduced lunch provided by the Los Angeles Unified School district.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data1.cde.ca.gov/dataquest/AcntRpt2010/2010APRSchAYPReport.aspx?allcds=19647331935519&df=2 |title=2010 Adequate Yearly Progress Chart |publisher=Data1.cde.ca.gov |date=2011-10-05 |accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref>\n\nThe Manual Arts Student Store is where students may purchase school supplies, [[snacks]], [[drinks]] and other items .\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Jon Arnett]], football player, member of [[College Football Hall of Fame]], class of 1952\n* [[Gus Arriola]], cartoonist and creator of ''[[Gordo (comic strip)|Gordo]]'', class of 1935\n* [[Verna Arvey]], musician and writer\n* [[Roy L. Ash]], (1918\u20132012), president of [[Litton Industries]], budget director<ref>Dennis McLellan,[http://www.latimes.com/news/obituaries/la-me-roy-ash-20120112,0,4487456.story Roy L. Ash dies at 93; former Litton president, budget director], ''Los Angeles Times'', January 12, 2012</ref>\n* [[Ted Bates (American football)|Ted Bates]], football player\n* [[Paul Blair (baseball)]], professional baseball player, Yankees, Orioles, Reds<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/b/blairpa01.shtml |title=Paul Blair Statistics and History |publisher=Baseball-Reference.com |date= |accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref>\n* [[Lyman Bostock]], professional baseball player, class of 1968\n* [[Steve Broussard]], former NFL running back, Class of 1985\n* [[Nacio Herb Brown]], songwriter, class of 1914\n* [[Yvonne Brathwaite Burke]], L.A. County Supervisor\n* [[Frank Capra]], film director\n* [[Leland Curtis]], artist, environmentalist, and Antarctic explorer\n* [[Jimmy Doolittle]], [[World War II]] aviator, class of 1914\n* [[Tom Fears]], Pro Football Hall of Fame for the [[Los Angeles Rams]], class of 1941\n* [[Earl C. Gay]] (1902\u201375), [[Los Angeles City Council]] member, 1933\u201345\n* [[Kathryn Grayson]], singer and film actress\n* [[Philip Guston]], artist, class of 1930\n* [[Robin Harris]], comedian and actor, class of 1971\n* [[Ed Heinemann]], self-taught aerospace engineer and aircraft designer for [[Douglas Aircraft Company]].\n* [[Virginia Jaramillo (artist)|Virginia Jaramillo]], painter\n* [[Jimmie Jones (running back)|Jimmie Jones]], football player\n* [[John Floyd Thomas Jr.]], serial killer\n* [[Reuben Kadish]], artist, class of 1930\n* [[Goodwin Knight]], 31st [[governor of California]], class of 1914\n* [[Leo K. Kuter]], film art director\n* [[Mittie Lawrence]], actress\n* [[Woodley Lewis]], football player\n* [[Ned Mathews]], football player\n* [[Gerson Mayen]], midfielder for [[Chivas USA]] of [[Major League Soccer]], class of 2005\n* [[Ross Murphyy]], self-taught entrepreneur; grad. two years ahead of his class    \n* [[Stanley Knowles]], [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[Member of parliament#Canada|Member of Parliament]] and [[New Democratic Party (Canada)|New Democratic Party]] [[House Leader]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Stebner |first1=Eleanor J. |year=1998 |title=The Education of Stanley Howard Knowles |url=http://www.mhs.mb.ca/docs/mb_history/36/knowles_sh.shtml |journal=Manitoba History |location=Winnipeg |publisher=Manitoba Historical Society |issue=36 |p=43 |issn=0226-5036 |accessdate=May 19, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Ernie Orsatti]], outfielder for the [[St. Louis Cardinals]]\n* [[Victor Orsatti]], [[Hollywood]] agent, film and television producer\n* [[Dwayne O'Steen]], football player\n* [[Jerry D. Page]], [[United States Air Force]] [[General]], class of 1932\n* [[Dwayne Polee]], former professional basketball player, class of 1981\n* [[Jackson Pollock]], artist, class of 1930 (left before graduation)<ref>[http://naples.cc.sunysb.edu/cas/pkhouse.nsf/pages/pollock ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080420183323/http://naples.cc.sunysb.edu/cas/pkhouse.nsf/pages/pollock |date=April 20, 2008 }}</ref>\n* [[Marie Prevost]], actress,<ref>{{cite book|last=Ankerich |first=Michael G. |title=Dangerous Curves atop Hollywood Heels: The Lives, Careers, and Misfortunes of 14 Hard-Luck Girls of the Silent Screen|year=2010|publisher=BearMano|isbn= 1-59393-605-2|page=283}}</ref> class of 1916\n* [[Rachel Robinson]], wife of [[MLB Hall of Fame]] inductee [[Jackie Robinson]]\n* [[Scott Stephen]], football player\n* [[Irving Stone]], author\n* [[Mark Ridley-Thomas]], [[Los Angeles Board of Supervisors]] member, class of 1972<ref>[http://dist26.casen.govoffice.com/index.asp?Type=B_BASIC&SEC=%7B81ABDC36-C342-4A85-ACAD-C7416F7633DD%7D ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071111134642/http://dist26.casen.govoffice.com/index.asp?Type=B_BASIC&SEC=%7B81ABDC36-C342-4A85-ACAD-C7416F7633DD%7D |date=November 11, 2007 }}</ref>\n* [[Eugene Selznick]], Hall of Fame volleyball player\n* [[Lawrence Tibbett]], baritone, [[Metropolitan Opera]], class of 1914\n* [[Paul Winfield]], actor\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.lausd.k12.ca.us/Manual_Arts_HS/ Manual Arts High School website]\n\n{{LAUSDDistrict7}}\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1910]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Unified School District schools]]\n[[Category:High schools in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in California]]\n[[Category:1910 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Exposition Park (Los Angeles neighborhood)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox school\n|name           = Manual Arts High School\n|native_name    =\n|logo           = \n|image          =MAHS IDENTITY logo.jpg\n|image_size     =230px\n|motto          = '''It Can Be Done'''\n|country        =\n|song           = \n|established    = 1910\n|type           =[[Public school (government funded)|Public]]\n|affiliation    =\n|district       = [[Los Angeles Unified School District]]\n|trustee        = \n|grades         = 9\u201312\n|campus         =\n|chairperson    = \n|president      =\n|principal      =  Erica Thomas-Minor\n|head of school =\n|dean           =\n|custodian      = \n|faculty        =\n|staff          = 72.84 (FTE)<ref name=NCES/>\n|ratio          = 19.33<ref name=NCES/>\n|students       = \n|enrollment     = 1,408 (2017-18)<ref name=NCES>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=0622710&SchoolPageNum=39&ID=062271003163|title=Manual Arts Senior High|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref>\n|athletics      =\n|conference     =Coliseum League<br>[[CIF Los Angeles City Section]]\n|colors         ={{Colorsample|#69359C}}{{Colorsample|#808080}} [[Royal Purple]] and [[Gray]]\n| mascot        = Tommy Toiler\n| mascot image  = \n|team_name      =Toilers\n|location       =4131 South Vermont Avenue<br/>[[Los Angeles, California]] 90037 <br />United States\n|streetaddress  =\n|coordinates    ={{Coord|34.0083|-118.29217|type:edu_region:US-CA|display=inline,title}}\n|website        ={{URL|http://www.mahs.org/}}\n}}\n'''Manual Arts High School''' is a secondary [[Public school (government funded)|public school]] in [[Los Angeles, California]]. When founded, Manual Arts was a vocational high school, but later{{When|date=March 2011}} converted to a traditional curriculum.\n\n==History==\nManual Arts High School was founded in 1910 in the middle of bean fields, one-half mile from the nearest bus stop. It was the third high school in Los Angeles, California after [[Los Angeles High School]] and [[Polytechnic High School (Los Angeles)|L.A. Polytechnic High School]], and is the oldest high school still on its original site in the Los Angeles Unified School District.  The school that would eventually become [[Abraham Lincoln High School (Los Angeles)|Lincoln High]] had been founded decades earlier but was still an elementary school at this time.\n\nOne of the school's first teachers was [[Ethel Percy Andrus]] (1911 - 1915).  In 1916 Dr. Andrus became California's first woman high school principal at Lincoln High School in East Los Angeles.  She later founded [[AARP]].\n\nAfter three semesters in an abandoned grammar school building, Manual Arts High School was opened on Vermont Avenue. After the [[1933 Long Beach earthquake]], the entire campus was rebuilt, constituting the present Manual Arts High School campus adjacent to the [[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]] and [[University of Southern California|USC]]. In 1995, \"The Arts\" became a [[Pacific Bell]] Education First Demonstration Site joining thirteen other demonstration sites in California, and in 1996 the school was named a [[California Distinguished School]]. In 1998, Manual Arts was officially granted [[Digital High School]] status.\n\nThe 2005\u20132006 school year opened with [[small learning communities]] (SLCs), three on each track totaling nine SLCs. Manual Arts was relieved by the opening of [[Santee Education Complex]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laschools.org/project-status/one-project?project_number=55A98010 |title=Project Details |publisher=Laschools.org |date=2011-10-13 |accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref>\n\n===West Adams High School===\nThe school was relieved in 2007 when [[West Adams Preparatory High School]] opened. During the same year, a section of the Manual Arts attendance zone was transferred to [[Belmont High School (Los Angeles)|Belmont High School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laschools.org/project-status/one-project?project_number=55.98021 |title=Project Details |publisher=Laschools.org |date=2011-10-13 |accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2008, the school became part of [[MLA Partner Schools]] through LAUSD's newly created iDesign Schools Division. MLA Partner Schools, in collaboration with West Ed, will operate Manual Arts on a 5-year performance contract approved by the LAUSD School Board.\n\nThe school was expected be relieved by Central Region High School 16 (which became [[Dr. Maya Angelou High School (Los Angeles, California)]]) when that school opened in 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laschools.org/project-status/one-project?project_number=56.40055 |title=Project Details |publisher=Laschools.org |date=2011-10-13 |accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref> and by Augustus Hawkins High School when that school opens in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laschools.org/project-status/one-project?project_number=55.98047 |title=Project Details |publisher=Laschools.org |date=2011-10-13 |accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2011\u20132012 school year, Manual Arts will return to a traditional school calendar schedule.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mahs.org/apps/news/show_news.jsp?REC_ID=180761&id=0 |title=Manual Arts Senior High School |publisher=Mahs.org |date=2011-03-11 |accessdate=2013-10-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004231200/http://www.mahs.org/apps/news/show_news.jsp?REC_ID=180761&id=0 |archivedate=2013-10-04 }}</ref> As a result, several of the school\u2019s small learning communities will be restructured and the number of security on campus will be reduced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-banks-20110517,0,7004032.column |title=Sandy Banks: At Manual Arts High, same goals but different methods|publisher=Latimes.com |date=2011-05-17 |accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref> The  ''''Blewett Football Field''' is named in honor of '''James Blewett''' who was a standout  Manual Arts football player and longtime Head coach with 9 Los Angeles City titles and 225 wins.\n\n==Student body==\nThe racial make-up of the school is mostly Latinos and African-Americans and the neighborhood surrounding the school reflects the same make-up.\n\nDuring the 2004\u20132005 school year, MAHS had 3,766 students,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.lausd.k12.ca.us/cgi-bin/fccgi.exe?w3exec=school.profile.content&which=8743 |title=School Profile (9-12) |publisher=Search.lausd.k12.ca.us |date=2009-09-16 |accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref> including:\n* 3,054 [[Hispanic]]s (81.1%)\n* 701 [[African-Americans]] (18.6%)\n* 5 [[White American]]s (1%)\n* 4 [[Asian American]]s (1%)\n* 2 [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native Americans]] (1%)\n\nAs of 2010, the dropout rate at Manual Arts was 68%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://idea.gseis.ucla.edu/educational-opportunity-report/2011/eor-hs-detail.php?cds_code=19647331935519 |title=UCLA IDEA Educational Opportunity Report |publisher=Idea.gseis.ucla.edu |date= |accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref>\n\nWith more than 90% of students qualifying for free or reduced lunch provided by the Los Angeles Unified School district.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data1.cde.ca.gov/dataquest/AcntRpt2010/2010APRSchAYPReport.aspx?allcds=19647331935519&df=2 |title=2010 Adequate Yearly Progress Chart |publisher=Data1.cde.ca.gov |date=2011-10-05 |accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref>\n\nThe Manual Arts Student Store is where students may purchase school supplies, [[snacks]], [[drinks]] and other items .\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Jon Arnett]], football player, member of [[College Football Hall of Fame]], class of 1952\n* [[Gus Arriola]], cartoonist and creator of ''[[Gordo (comic strip)|Gordo]]'', class of 1935\n* [[Verna Arvey]], musician and writer\n* [[Roy L. Ash]], (1918\u20132012), president of [[Litton Industries]], budget director<ref>Dennis McLellan,[http://www.latimes.com/news/obituaries/la-me-roy-ash-20120112,0,4487456.story Roy L. Ash dies at 93; former Litton president, budget director], ''Los Angeles Times'', January 12, 2012</ref>\n* [[Ted Bates (American football)|Ted Bates]], football player\n* [[Paul Blair (baseball)]], professional baseball player, Yankees, Orioles, Reds<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/b/blairpa01.shtml |title=Paul Blair Statistics and History |publisher=Baseball-Reference.com |date= |accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref>\n* [[Lyman Bostock]], professional baseball player, class of 1968\n* [[Steve Broussard]], former NFL running back, Class of 1985\n* [[Nacio Herb Brown]], songwriter, class of 1914\n* [[Yvonne Brathwaite Burke]], L.A. County Supervisor\n* [[Frank Capra]], film director\n* [[Leland Curtis]], artist, environmentalist, and Antarctic explorer\n* [[Jimmy Doolittle]], [[World War II]] aviator, class of 1914\n* [[Tom Fears]], Pro Football Hall of Fame for the [[Los Angeles Rams]], class of 1941\n* [[Earl C. Gay]] (1902\u201375), [[Los Angeles City Council]] member, 1933\u201345\n* [[Kathryn Grayson]], singer and film actress\n* [[Philip Guston]], artist, class of 1930\n* [[Robin Harris]], comedian and actor, class of 1971\n* [[Ed Heinemann]], self-taught aerospace engineer and aircraft designer for [[Douglas Aircraft Company]].\n* [[Virginia Jaramillo (artist)|Virginia Jaramillo]], painter\n* [[Jimmie Jones (running back)|Jimmie Jones]], football player\n* [[John Floyd Thomas Jr.]], serial killer\n* [[Reuben Kadish]], artist, class of 1930\n* [[Goodwin Knight]], 31st [[governor of California]], class of 1914\n* [[Leo K. Kuter]], film art director\n* [[Mittie Lawrence]], actress\n* [[Woodley Lewis]], football player\n* [[Ned Mathews]], football player\n* [[Gerson Mayen]], midfielder for [[Chivas USA]] of [[Major League Soccer]], class of 2005\n* [[Stanley Knowles]], [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[Member of parliament#Canada|Member of Parliament]] and [[New Democratic Party (Canada)|New Democratic Party]] [[House Leader]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Stebner |first1=Eleanor J. |year=1998 |title=The Education of Stanley Howard Knowles |url=http://www.mhs.mb.ca/docs/mb_history/36/knowles_sh.shtml |journal=Manitoba History |location=Winnipeg |publisher=Manitoba Historical Society |issue=36 |p=43 |issn=0226-5036 |accessdate=May 19, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Ernie Orsatti]], outfielder for the [[St. Louis Cardinals]]\n* [[Victor Orsatti]], [[Hollywood]] agent, film and television producer\n* [[Dwayne O'Steen]], football player\n* [[Jerry D. Page]], [[United States Air Force]] [[General]], class of 1932\n* [[Dwayne Polee]], former professional basketball player, class of 1981\n* [[Jackson Pollock]], artist, class of 1930 (left before graduation)<ref>[http://naples.cc.sunysb.edu/cas/pkhouse.nsf/pages/pollock ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080420183323/http://naples.cc.sunysb.edu/cas/pkhouse.nsf/pages/pollock |date=April 20, 2008 }}</ref>\n* [[Marie Prevost]], actress,<ref>{{cite book|last=Ankerich |first=Michael G. |title=Dangerous Curves atop Hollywood Heels: The Lives, Careers, and Misfortunes of 14 Hard-Luck Girls of the Silent Screen|year=2010|publisher=BearMano|isbn= 1-59393-605-2|page=283}}</ref> class of 1916\n* [[Rachel Robinson]], wife of [[MLB Hall of Fame]] inductee [[Jackie Robinson]]\n* [[Scott Stephen]], football player\n* [[Irving Stone]], author\n* [[Mark Ridley-Thomas]], [[Los Angeles Board of Supervisors]] member, class of 1972<ref>[http://dist26.casen.govoffice.com/index.asp?Type=B_BASIC&SEC=%7B81ABDC36-C342-4A85-ACAD-C7416F7633DD%7D ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071111134642/http://dist26.casen.govoffice.com/index.